text: @grok - that is incorrect. Gardasil 9 trial gave 306 people placebo after full series of Gardasil 4. In Gardasil 4's trial, controls received aluminum adjuvant, AAHS, except 320 people labeled "Saline Placebo" that actually received all vaccine ingredients except antigens and AAHS. Across trials, 2-3% receiving vaccine or aluminum adjuvant (used to induce autoimmunity) had a suspected autoimmune disorder.

text: Okay, I spent 3 1/2 days in the hospital again, not sure if I am okay yet. They said my spleen is dying off. About 25% is gone, and that's okay, I am going on Eliquis to try to get the blood flowing again. If that helps the pain may leave. It's my left side ribcage, and upper left arm. I see my primary care Dr. again on the 12th, and a hematologist in three months. Wish me luck. If i get my way ai will see my primary care before the 12th.

text: "Off the Cuff" - Markets were in "buy the dip" mode all day recouping nearly half of yesterday's drop even as there is uncertainty surrounding the tariffs that have been implemented since the Supreme Court is now in a hearing to discuss their validity. Even if the Supreme Court rules against them, there are still other ways they can be implemented. The Russell 2000 small cap index led the way higher today up 1.54%, the Nasdaq rose 0.65%, the S&P gained 0.37%, and the Dow advanced 0.48%. The VIX fell by over 5% back down to 18. Yields jumped up today after strong employment data with the 10-year yield closing up at 4.16%. WTI oil closed just below $60 per barrel. Eight of the eleven major sectors finished higher on the day. The sub-sectors outperforming the Russell today were Clean Energy, Blockchain, Semiconductors, Datacenters, and many more up 0.25-1.5%. Earnings of note after the close are from AppLovin, Arm Holdings, CF Industries, DoorDash, Dutch Bros, e.l.f. Beauty, Fortinet, HubSpot, Lyft, and Qualcomm. Earnings to watch for in the morning are from AstraZeneca, ConocoPhillips, Cummins, Datadog, DuPont, Granite Construction, Hyatt, NRG Energy, Parker-Hannifin, Ralph Lauren, Rockwell Automation, Tapestry, TripAdvisor, and Vistra. We will hear from a couple of more Fed governors during the day tomorrow. As always, if you have any questions regarding the information in this email, please don't hesitate to contact me Content curated and written daily by Douglas Emitte Follow me on LinkedIn for "Off the Cuff" and other important news

text: Thereâ€™s a quiet debate that weâ€™ve been having in rural America. It will never make the national news, and it won't affect most of the population, but it's leaving small towns looking for answers. â€¢ Immigration. â€¢ But not the kind youâ€™re thinking aboutâ€¦ ... stick with me. â€¢ See, weâ€™re quick to talk about immigrants from other countries. â€¢ And truth be told, even when I donâ€™t agree with the tone some folks take, I usually agree with the premise: If youâ€™re going to come to America, learn the culture, understand the language, honor the heritage, respect the values, revere the flag, and become an American. â€¢ Its confusing to see people run from a broken nation just to demand America become the nation they ran from. â€¢ It hurts to see people wave a foreign flag that was worth leaving while taking advantage of the blessings found under this new one. â€¢ For generations, immigrants came here understanding the unspoken sacred rule: Becoming American meant letting something old die away so something greater could be born. â€¢ But hereâ€™s the undercurrent nobody wants to talk aboutâ€¦ â€¢ Americans are doing the exact same thing to each other as you read this post. â€¢ Follow me. â€¢ Over the past number of years, there has been a mass migration, not from overseas, but from the big cities into the country. â€¢ People wanted space. Quiet. Kind neighbors. A place where the air felt cleaner, where the world felt slower. â€¢ And rural communities, generous as they always are, opened their arms wide. â€¢ These new immigrants moved into rural communities and talked about how much they loved the sound of driving on gravel roads, looking up into the sky and seeing stars, and how they enjoyed the feeling of soft soil under their feet. â€¢ But now? The murmurs are happeningâ€¦ â€¢ Now some of these same newcomers are annoyed â€¦. â€¢ â€œThe grocery store is too far.â€ â€œThereâ€™s nothing for the kids to do.â€ â€œWe need more amenities, more activities, more, more, more.â€ â€¢ They left one worldâ€¦ then came here and started demanding the old world be rebuilt around them. â€¢ Tell me how thatâ€™s any different from an immigrant protesting America while waving the flag of the country he fled? â€¢ You moved here because it was different. You loved the charm. You loved the peace. You loved the simplicity. â€¢ But now that you live here, you have forgotten why you left "there". â€¢ You want a small town to behave like a big city while still pretending to be a small town? â€¢ Impossible. â€¢ So if youâ€™re a transplant to a rural community, hereâ€™s the truth, spoken with love, and maybe a little annoyance: Learn the language of the land. Honor the history. Respect the sacrifices of the people who built it long before you arrived. And assimilate. â€¢ Growth is good when itâ€™s wholesome. Everyone should be "pro wholesome growth". â€¢ But forced growth? â€¢ Thatâ€™s how you kill the very spirit you came looking for. â€¢ Forced growth is how roots snaps instead of growing deeper. â€¢ So I encourage you, Breathe the country air. Embrace the slower pace. Appreciate the trade-offs. And let the community grow at the pace it was meant to. â€¢ Because if you liked the city life so muchâ€¦ â€¦ you shouldâ€™ve stayed in the city.

Credit: Universal Pictures/ Courtesy: Everett *The Mummy*, Stephen Sommersâ€™ rip-roaring reboot of the 1932 Boris Karloff classic, turned star Brendan Fraser into an action hero upon its release in 1999. The horror-comedy-action hybrid wasnâ€™t a sure bet. The resurrection of the Universal monster franchise toiled in development hell for decades, with genre icons like George Romero and Clive Barker attached at various points. The film earned over $400 million worldwide and received an Oscar nomination for visual effects. In the years since, there have been two sequels, a spinoff franchise, and a Tom Cruise-led reboot. Now, a new *Mummy* movie with Fraser and costar Rachel Weisz is in the works with Radio Silence, the filmmaking team behind horror hits *Ready or Not* (2019) and *Scream VI* (2023). As we wait to see how that project takes shape, let's have a look at what the cast of *The Mummy* has been up to over the past 25 years. text: Earnings seasons for second quarter is over and recent macro measure seems to have started paying off for India Inc. India Inc delivered a mixed but encouraging Q2FY26, with revenue rising 9% and profits jumping 16% year-on-year. Ex-banks and financials, profit growth surged 22%, supported by a favourable base. Refineries emerged as the biggest growth engine thanks to stronger GRMs and lower crude prices. Cement and steel posted exceptional performance driven by demand recovery, pricing improvement and operating leverage. Auto benefited from exports, festive demand and GST 2.0, while pharma maintained solid momentum despite nearing loss of Revlimid generic exclusivity. Banks saw stable asset quality, though FY26 remains soft. FMCG and IT were clear weak spots. In this episode, Sudip Bandopadhyay breaks down sector trends and what H2FY26 means for markets and investors. Refineries emerged as the biggest growth engine thanks to stronger GRMs and lower crude prices. Cement and steel posted exceptional performance driven by demand recovery, pricing improvement and operating leverage. Auto benefited from exports, festive demand and GST 2.0, while pharma maintained solid momentum despite nearing loss of the cancer treatment drug generic exclusivity. Banks saw stable asset quality, though FY26 remains soft. FMCG and IT were clear weak spots. In this episode, Sudip Bandopadhyay breaks down sector trends and what H2FY26 means for markets and investors. Watch LIVE: https://youtube.com/live/BMK-CrdLkcI | #Q2FY26 #IndiaInc #Earnings #MarketOutlook #CementSector

text: #MARESBayanihanForHealthğŸª§Parents engage in crucial dialogue on School-Based Immunization at MARES Parents and guardians of Grades 1 and 4 learners gathered at the Manuel A. Roxas Elementary School Gymnasium on November 14, 2025, for an orientation on the upcoming School-Based Immunization Program led by the Department of Health (DOH) and the Local Government Unit. The session aimed to inform parents about the Measles-Rubella (MR) and Tetanus-Diphtheria (Td) vaccines for Grade 1 and the Human Papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine for Grade 4 girls, all scheduled for administration on December 4, 2025. Representatives from the Mini-Forest Health Center facilitated the discussions to ensure parents understood the importance, procedures, and safety of the immunization process. â€œThis orientation is meant to empower you with knowledge,â€ said Maâ€™am Nancy B. Lopez, school principal, as she welcomed attendees. â€œWe encourage you to listen, ask, and clarify anything that concerns your childâ€™s health.â€ She emphasized that protecting children from preventable diseases begins with informed decisions and active participation of parents. The orientation proceeded with detailed presentations from health experts, addressing both the medical and procedural aspects of the program. Nurse II Karla Eunice C. Rondez explained that vaccines such as MR, Td, and HPV play a vital role in safeguarding children from serious illnesses, noting that Grade 1 learners will receive booster immunizations, while Grade 4 girls will be given HPV shots to prevent cervical cancer later in life. Meanwhile, Nurse II Kathrina Jasmin M. Orilla walked parents through the Parentâ€™s Consent Form, stressing the importance of completing it accurately for the safety and documentation of the immunization process. The School-Based Immunization Program is a nationwide health initiative in partnership with DepEd, DOH, and local government units to increase vaccine coverage among school-age children. It aims to curb outbreaks of measles, rubella, diphtheria, tetanus, and cervical cancerâ€”diseases that remain significant public health concerns in the country. An open forum concluded the session, giving parents the opportunity to voice their concerns and seek clarifications before the December 4 immunization schedule. Despite uncertainties, many expressed appreciations for the schoolâ€™s effort to guide families toward informed health decisions. With strengthened collaboration among the school community, health authorities, and parents, MARES continues to champion the well-being and protection of its learners.

â€œ December 13th 2016, he received dtap, hib, polio, hepatitis an and influenza when he was 18 and half months old and 24 pounds. I remember 12/13/16 like it was yesterday. The pediatrician asked me about milestones and language and I shared something funny that happened. Luka and I were at the grocery store and he was sitting in the front of the cart. When she showed me the vaccines he would get that day, I said, â€œthat seems like a lot, are you sure thatâ€™s ok?â€ She looked at them and told me he had all of them before and he had no reaction, right? I said, â€œno I guess he didnâ€™t.â€

At the grocery store before 12/13/16 was the last time I heard my child say, â€œgo, go, go!â€

â€œDays later, he suffered physical and neurological injuries as evidenced by pictures and videos of a left sided facial droop and left sided body weakness. I didnâ€™t realize at the time it was a vaccine reaction. He was teething very heavily, had a mild fever, quiet, lethargic, and withdrawn and just generally not feeling well. But later in January, my mom called me in a panic and said, â€œthereâ€™s something wrong with Luka!â€ She watched him 2 days a week while I worked. I had a babysitter the other days and when I asked the sitter, she noticed the same issues as my mom. I just knew something happened to him when he shut down, stopped responding to his name, staring episodes, and stopped saying words. My baby was ahead of the curve with most developmental milestones then suddenly and dramatically regressed after that round of vaccines.

â€œI called the pediatrician and early intervention crying and saying I donâ€™t know if he hit his head or if he is traumatized over his nana but heâ€™s different and everyone is concerned. â€œC urrently, my son has no functional language and he is in speech therapy since March 2017, he is frequently ill, spikes fevers for no reason, sweats profusely, has intermittent left arm weakness, small pupils all the time, signs of possible asthma and food allergies, nystagmus which was recently diagnosed and strange spots on his sclera that werenâ€™t there pre-vaccine injury.

text: âœ¨ FRONTERA SUMMER INTERNSHIP - STUDENT HIGHLIGHT âœ¨ Hi! My name is Raymond Alkakooz. I am a third-year student double majoring in Biomedical Sciences and Global Health. I aspire to be a physician for many reasons. From my journey from Iraq to Phoenix, to serving my community as a first responder, to seeing firsthand the health disparities that affect underserved populations, being a doctor has always been my calling. Witnessing the effects of gang violence, homelessness, and severe illness reinforced my duty to deliver the best care with empathy. Medicine, as a symbol, is incorruptible, enduring, and the purest form of human connection. This is why I pursued both degreesâ€”to become a more well-rounded provider with biological knowledge and cultural inclusiveness. It has been an honor to work under Tomas NuÃ±o, PhD, at the Arizona Prevention Research Center and the Department of Epidemiology and Biostatistics at the University of Arizona. During the FRONTERA Summer Internship I researched quantitative and qualitative studies on HPV vaccine use, knowledge, and beliefs among U.S. southern border communities. I gained insights into vaccine hesitancy, cultural factors contributing to disparities, and how culturally tailored interventions can improve uptake. My favorite part of the program was the clinical experience. I externed as a population health technician at El Rio Health, a Federally Qualified Health Center. I conducted outreach for overdue A1C and diabetes retinopathy patients, helped providers prepare for appointments, and coordinated follow-ups with other clinics. A memorable includes receiving recognition from CDC scientific officer Rosalind Carter for my HPV research insights and participating in a clinic trip to deliver free medical care in Puerto PeÃ±asco, Sonora, Mexico, with students from the University of Arizona College of Medicine - Tucson. Apply for the 2026 FRONTERA Summer Internship. Application closes on February 20. https://bit.ly/4oxn3Ru

text: PRESS RELEASE World Cervical Cancer Day: NAPHDA and Pathfinder International Launch Free HPV Screening Initiative In an empowering initiative commemorating World Cervical Cancer Day, the Nasarawa State Primary Healthcare Development Agency (NAPHDA), in partnership with Pathfinder International, has launched a comprehensive free cervical cancer screening program for women and vaccination against the Human Papilloma Virus (HPV) for adolescent girls in Kwandere, Lafia. The program was inaugurated by Her Excellency Hajiya Salifat Abdullahi Sule, the First Lady of Nasarawa State, who made a passionate appeal for women to take advantage of this opportunity to protect their health. "Health is wealth. Let us help ourselves by utilizing this free cervical cancer screening provided by the state government and our partners for the well-being of our children," she urged. The First Lady emphasized the importance of regular cervical cancer screening and ensuring that young girls receive their HPV vaccinations. She encouraged women to seek medical attention promptly if they experience any symptoms, highlighting that early detection can save lives. Dr. Gaza Gowona, the Commissioner of Health, represented by Permanent Secretary Dr. John Damina, reaffirmed the state government's commitment to ensuring that vaccines and necessary medical equipment are readily available at designated treatment centers for the beneficiaries. He lauded the First Lady for her unwavering dedication to addressing health issues and praised the Executive Secretary of NAPHDA, Dr. Usman Iskilu Saleh, for spearheading the cervical cancer screening initiative. Acknowledging the First Lady's significant role in the success of previous health initiatives, including the measles and rubella vaccination campaign, the Executive Secretary noted that these efforts positioned Nasarawa State at the forefront of vaccine administration. He extended gratitude to the Kwandere community and their traditional ruler, Sangarin Kwandere, for their support. Fatima Maho, State Coordinator of Pathfinder International, expressed delight in the collaboration with the state government to promote awareness and encourage HPV vaccination. "My final call to you is to ensure you screen, educate, and vaccinate," she urged, assuring the community that subsequent screenings would follow in the coming year. Dr. Bosede Ezekiel, the World Health Organization (WHO) State Coordinator, speaking on behalf of other Partiners commended the state government for creating a supportive environment for partners to effectively assist the community. She praised Pathfinder International for their significant contributions to the cervical cancer screening and HPV immunization efforts. Marvellous Andrew, a beneficiary of the free medical outreach, expressed her gratitude towards the state government and Pathfinder International for launching the timely program, which would allow her to ascertain her cervical cancer status. This vital medical outreach initiative aims to screen over 100 women in the state, with immediate treatment options available for those who test positive for cervical cancer. Through this collaborative effort, NAPHDA and Pathfinder International are taking significant steps toward reducing cervical cancer risk and promoting public health in Nasarawa State. Signed Aminu Isiaka H (ANIPR). Information and Public Relations Officer NAPHDA 24TH NOVEMBER 2025.

It's been a long day. Kyle's scans are back. Forrest got scared but did okay once we convinced him we weren't there for him. It started out with us meeting with the Dr. Then we went to another part of the hospital for Kyle to have labs drawn, Kristin went with him while Forrest and I waited. They came out, we then had lunch and headed back to the oncology department. Then the news. My sister Sara was able to shade the mass that we're dealing with so it'll be easier to see. Kyle goes in this coming Thursday for his port, he'll then be admitted, then they start the chemo. He'll be there for 5 days, immune system completely suppressed but they're hoping he'll be home either before or on Thanksgiving day. This was like Dejavu all over again. The flashbacks I had were incredible. Kyle's mass was compared to "jello", it's a mass but it's not solid. We go in on Thursday, Kyle will have his port put in, then he'll be admitted. Chemo will start as soon as they're ready. My son will lose his hair. They're putting him on Ifosimide and Adriamycin in hopes to shrink or kill the tumor so it can be removed. As for the blood clot, he's to remain on Eliquis in hopes that it'll destroy the clot and his system will absorb it. They won't put in a graft to catch it because all that will do is create another clot. They're hoping Kyle will be home by Thanksgiving. He'll have to do this, like Forrest and me, every 3 weeks. One week inpatient, 2 weeks out, only where footrest and I come home, he'll stay. We're going to have to be extremely careful because he'll be immunocompromised. Even now, if Kristin and I take Forrest to the store, we hear a cough and we still rush Forrest as far away as possible in the other direction or we just leave. Kristin will stay with Kyle unless we trade off. Forrest and Kyle are the utmost priority. If Forrest will tolerate it, we'll stay with Kyle. We have a rule, we stay together, no matter what. Please pray for us, especially Kristin, she needs strength. We need her tested too Kyle Penquite Kristin N Lukemire-Penquite

text: Whoa-zempic! â€‹ The next wave of obesity drugs is pushing the limits of weight loss. Roxanne Khamsi November 19, 2025 Medical weight loss might be on the verge of a further revolution. For starters, people will likely have the option of taking a new class of medications that seem to have fewer bothersome side effects, such as nauseaâ€”which affects about half the people on Ozempic and similar drugs. Those now-familiar medications target a pathway involving the appetite-regulating hormone GLP-1; the new ones target cell receptors for a different hormone, amylin. AstraZeneca, Eli Lilly, Zealand Pharma, and, of course, Novo Nordisk, which makes Ozempic, are all testing amylin-based obesity drugs. And if the increasing number of new weight-loss medications seems hard to choose from, you might not have to pick just one. Some medications in development, such as CagriSema, go one step beyond, combining components that target amylin and GLP-1 to make even more powerful drugs. In a recent trial, individuals with obesity who took an amylin-based drug called cagrilintide lost about 12 percent of their weight over the course of 16 months. Those on semaglutide, the active ingredient in Ozempic, lost about 15 percent. Those taking CagriSema lost, on average, more than 20 percent. (By comparison, bariatric surgery, a dramatic procedure that reconfigures the digestive system, can cause a person to lose about 30 percent of their weightâ€”but it comes with the possibility of serious complications such as hernias and life-threatening infections.) These new combination drugs are pressing weight loss far enough past the limits of existing drugs that the field of obesity research is facing an unprecedented question: How far should medical weight loss go? Thomas Lutz, who is known by his contemporaries as the â€œamylin guy,â€ has been conducting amylin research at the University of Zurich since the early 1990s, beginning only a few years after amylin had been isolated and characterized in pancreatic cells. Some scientists looked at the molecule with suspicion because it had been isolated in deposits within the pancreas of diabetic patients. Lutz and others helped show that it could reduce appetite in animals. But, perhaps partly because of the lingering mystery of why amylin deposits occur in the body, he found that the wider field took quite a while to get interested in his and other amylin researchersâ€™ work. â€œWe were probably considered outsiders by many others in the field,â€ Lutz told me. Most of his peers were focused on GLP-1, or leptin, or other peptidesâ€”molecules made of the same building blocks as proteins, but smaller. â€œNot many labs really focused on amylin.â€ The compound has been used as a drug in the past, Lutz said, albeit in less potent incarnations. Pramlintide, an analogue of amylin, was approved by the FDA for treating diabetes in 2005. The formulation degrades rapidly enough that it has to be injected before every major meal, though; cagrilintide sticks around longer and is injected only once a week. Pramlintide also doesnâ€™t have as big an effect on weight loss compared with the more recent array of amylin drugs. In one trial, twice as many people receiving it lost at least 5 percent of their body weight after four months, relative to those receiving the placebo. But thatâ€™s a modest effect. Amylin is just one of a bevy of hormones involved in metabolism that pharmaceutical companies are thinking of using as components in future weight-loss therapies. â€œCompanies are kind of going down the list,â€ looking at peptides that are secreted after meals and might have commercial potential, Kevin Hall, a metabolism scientist and co-author of the new book Food Intelligence, told me. There are drugs in the works that join the action of GLP-1 with that of GIP, a hormone released from the upper intestine, despite uncertainty about how GIP influences appetite. Some companies are looking at drugs based on the hormone glucagon. Others are investigating peptide YY, a gut hormone that signals to the brain that a meal has been consumed. Famke Janssen on Amsterdam Empire and recording that catchy 'Forever Pour Toujours' music video: 'It was tough' The &34;XMen&34; and &34;GoldenEye&34; alum talks all about &34;Forever Pour Toujours,&34; her catchy single she recorded for the Dutch Netflix drama. By Nick Romano :maxbytes(150000):stripicc()/NicholasRomanoauthorphotoadc9b60763e34711935cbf7b3d768d24. The "X-Men" and "GoldenEye" alum talks all about "Forever Pour Toujours," her catchy single she recorded for the Dutch Netflix drama. Famke Janssen on Amsterdam Empire and recording that catchy 'Forever Pour Toujours' music video: 'It was tough' The "X-Men" and "GoldenEye" alum talks all about "Forever Pour Toujours," her catchy single she recorded for the Dutch Netflix drama. By Nick Romano Nick Romano is a senior editor at ** with 15 years of journalism experience covering entertainment. His work previously appeared in *Vanity Fair*, Vulture, IGN, and more. EW's editorial guidelines October 30, 2025 2:33 p.m. ET Leave a Comment Famke Janssen as Betty Jonkers on 'Amsterdam Empire'. Credit: - Famke Janssen is now, basically, a pop star, having recorded a professional single and music video for the Dutch Netflix drama *Amsterdam Empire*. - The actress talks about how "tough" it was to train in singing and dancing to pull it off. - "Betty is so unapologetically who she is," she says of her character. "Pour toujours, pour toujours / Forever pour toujours." The song is such an earworm, you'll likely hum it to yourself in the days after watching Netflix's *Amsterdam Empire*, a new Dutch drama starring Famke Janssen. The actress of *X-Men*, *Taken*, and *GoldenEye* portrays Betty Jonkers, marking her first time acting in Dutch since leaving the Netherlands to pursue modeling in her teens. Story wise, this ex-pop diva is out to steal her former husband's thriving marijuana coffee shop business after he left her for a younger woman he impregnated. Among Betty's claims to fame is a hit 1990s single called "Forever Pour Toujours." Janssen and Netherlands-based musician Palmbomen (a.k.a. Kai Hugo) professionally recorded and released the song through Netflix music. The star then also shot a music video. "Isn't it so catchy? It's hilarious, I know," Janssen tells **. "While we were filming, I was being trained for singing and dancing to make the video. And I kept pushing it, going, 'I'm so busy. Can we do it at the end of the shoot?' I thought, 'I need more time.' I love to dance. Trust me, it's one of my hobbies, but I've never been trained." Betty Jonkers (Famke Janssen) rolls up to the Amsterdam Music Awards on 'Amsterdam Empire'. She also doesn't consider herself a professional singer, even though "Forever Pour Toujours" is now on Apple Music and Spotify. She remembers, however, singing karaoke with the cast of *X-Men*, including James Marsden, who played Cyclops to her Jean Grey and previously commented on his costar's "beautiful" singing voice. Janssen remembers being in Tokyo with Marsden and his wife, Lisa Linde, where they would hit the karaoke bars. "I'm not speaking out of turn, she knew this: She had a terrible voice, he had the most incredible voice," she recalls. "They would do duets together and stuff like that. It was hilarious. But I've always been incredibly intimidated by singing." Famke Janssen details her struggles with fame: 'The press always wins' James Marsden calls 'Avengers: Doomsday' return a homecoming to 'X-Men' role She worked with choreographer Vincent Vianen, whom she describes as "meticulous" with the '90s-inspired movements. "It was tough. He had to be tough on me and he had to be very strict and firm," Janssen says. "I practiced. All day, whenever I was on set, people would see me in the background doing small moves." The Running Man was one such dance move she had to learn, since the video took inspiration from '90s hip-hop. "We started doing it on a slower speed in the beginning," she remembers. "Just try to do the Running Man. Do it at normal speed and then do it at the speed of the song ["Forever Pour Toujours"]. It was a challenge, but I did it." Famke Janssen on 'Amsterdam Empire'. The tone of *Amsterdam Empire* is an enjoyable concoction of *Breaking Bad*-esque drama (instead of blue meth, it's weed) but also *Real Housewives*-level camp. In one of her more soapy, theatrical moments, Janssen's Betty arrives by boat to the Amsterdam Music Awards to upend a big work moment for her ex's new lover. Nico Moolenaar, Bart Uytdenhouwen, and Piet Matthys created *Amsterdam Empire*, which Janssen also executive produces with Moolenaar. She says they were very specific in terms of the sought-after vibe. Janssen saw the character as a celebrity who believes music was a big part of her life once upon a time, even though it was a relatively small component in reality. "Betty is so unapologetically who she is," Janssen describes, "claiming space, asking for attention, dressing big, all of that. It's not at all the way I am in life. Just because of the fact that she was this one-hit wonder and she can't quite let go of it, there is that larger-than-life campy aspect to her personality, but I wanted to ground it in reality." ***Get your daily dose of entertainment news, celebrity updates, and what to watch with our EW Dispatch newsletter.*** Technically, Betty isn't a one-hit wonder. Janssen confirms she recorded multiple songs for *Amsterdam Empire*. "They kept throwing things at me, like, 'Did you wanna go to the studio?' And I go, 'Sure! Let's do it.'" Look out for that album release! *Amsterdam Empire* is available now on Netfllix.** Original Article on Source Source: "EW TV" Read More Source: TV #ShowBiz #Sports #Politics #Celebrities #Lifestyle November 01, 2025 at 10:01AM via @ALPHA MAG

Janssen saw the character as a celebrity who believes music was a big part of her life once upon a time, even though it was a relatively small component in reality. "Betty is so unapologetically who she is," Janssen describes, "claiming space, asking for attention, dressing big, all of that. It's not at all the way I am in life. Just because of the fact that she was this one-hit wonder and she can't quite let go of it, there is that larger-than-life campy aspect to her personality, but I wanted to ground it in reality." ***Get your daily dose of entertainment news, celebrity updates, and what to watch with our EW Dispatch newsletter.*** Technically, Betty isn't a one-hit wonder. Janssen confirms she recorded multiple songs for *the Dutch Netflix drama*. "They kept throwing things at me, like, 'Did you wanna go to the studio?' And I go, 'Sure! Let's do it.'" text: She had 12 children and a PhDâ€”when widowhood threatened to end her career, she revolutionized how America worked, one brilliant insight at a time. Most people see problems. Lillian Moller Gilbreth saw systems waiting to be perfected. Born in 1878 in Oakland, California, Lillian was the eldest of nine childrenâ€”shy, brilliant, and hungry for knowledge in an era that told women their minds were decorative. Her father believed college was wasted on daughters. She proved him spectacularly wrong. By 1900, she had graduated from UC Berkeley. Then earned a master's in literature. Then, in 1915, she completed her PhD in psychology from Brown Universityâ€”becoming one of the first women in America to earn a doctorate, at a time when most universities wouldn't even admit women. But Lillian didn't pursue psychology to analyze emotions. She wanted to understand human motion, efficiency, and dignity in work. She married Frank Gilbreth, a self-taught engineer as restless and innovative as she was. Together, they became pioneers of motion studyâ€”the science of making work faster, safer, and more humane. While Frank timed workers with stopwatches, Lillian watched their faces, their posture, their exhaustion. She asked the question few male engineers considered: Can work be made kinder? They filmed workers performing tasks frame by frame, identified inefficiencies, and created "therbligs"â€”17 fundamental motions that comprise all human labor. Their methods transformed factories, hospitals, and eventually homes across America. They wrote books, lectured internationally, and raised twelve children. Their household became a working laboratoryâ€”later immortalized in the book and film "Cheaper by the Dozen." Then, in 1924, tragedy struck. Frank died suddenly of a heart attack at age 55. Lillian was 46, with eleven children still at home and a career the industrial world refused to recognize without her husband's name attached. Clients canceled contracts. Factory doors closed. The engineering establishment dismissed herâ€”woman, widow, motherâ€”as unqualified. She could have retreated into grief and motherhood. Instead, she reinvented herself. If men wouldn't hire her for their factories, she would redesign their world anywayâ€”starting with the spaces they'd never bothered to study: homes. Lillian interviewed over 4,000 women to understand their daily labor. What she discovered was revolutionary: kitchens were designed by men who had never cooked a meal in their lives. So she redesigned them with scientific precision. She pioneered the work triangle concept and advocated for optimal counter heights based on human ergonomics. She created the mobile workstation and pushed for better-designed kitchen tools that reduced repetitive strain. She studied how homemakers moved through their days and eliminated thousands of unnecessary steps. Her insights influenced refrigerator design, including interior organization. While specific inventions like the foot-pedal trash can are sometimes attributed to her (though documentation is unclear), her broader impact is undeniable: she transformed domestic work from invisible drudgery into a field worthy of engineering excellence. But Lillian's legacy extends far beyond kitchens. In 1935, she became the first female engineering professor at Purdue University. She advised multiple U.S. Presidents on workplace efficiency and rehabilitation. She consulted for General Electric, Macy's, and Johnson & Johnson. During World War II, she helped design workspaces accessible for disabled veterans. She worked into her eighties, earned over 20 honorary degrees, became the first woman elected to the National Academy of Engineering, and received the prestigious Hoover Medal for distinguished public service. Her philosophy was elegantly simple: "Good design should serve people. Efficiency should reduce suffering, not increase it." Lillian Moller Gilbreth didn't just study workâ€”she humanized it. She proved that engineering without empathy is incomplete. That efficiency means nothing if it breaks the people performing the labor. That a woman with a PhD and twelve children could reshape American industry precisely because she understood both intellect and care. She was called "the mother of modern management" and "the first lady of engineering." But perhaps her greatest achievement was this: she refused to let the world's limitations become her own. When doors closed, she built new ones. When her expertise was dismissed, she found new problems to solve. When widowhood could have ended her career, she made it her launching point. Lillian Moller Gilbreth had 12 children and a brilliant mindâ€”and she used both to prove that genius doesn't require choosing between family and achievement. It requires refusing to accept that you must.

text: Healthcare in costs in America is a tragedy ğŸ¤¬ğŸ¤¬ğŸ¤¬ğŸ¤¬ğŸ¤¬ A U.S. government study found that in 2022, U.S. drug prices were on average ~229 % of Canadian prices (i.e., Canadian prices were about 44 % of what Americans paid) for the same drugs. Another review noted that for brand-name drugs, U.S. prices can be ~3 to 4 times higher than in Canada (or higher, depending on the specific drug). For example: Eliquis (a blood thinner) costs in the U.S. ~$1,668 for 180 tablets, while in Canada the lowest listed price was ~$370. Jardiance (for diabetes) cost ~$1,845 in the U.S. for 90 tablets versus ~$290 in Canada. An analysis found that Rinvoq (for Crohnâ€™s/ulcerative colitis) is ~$11,915 in the U.S. vs ~$1,749.95 in Canada â€” roughly 7Ã— the Canadian price. âš ï¸ Examples of drugs with large U.S.â€“Canada price gaps Eliquis: ~4.5Ã— higher in the U.S. vs Canada. Jardiance: ~6Ã—+ higher in the U.S. vs Canada. Rinvoq: ~7Ã— higher. In a broader list: Latuda (an antipsychotic) 90 tablets cost ~$4,628 in U.S., ~$520 in Canada (~89 % cheaper in Canada). Synthroid (for hypothyroidism) cost ~$114 in U.S. vs ~$44 in Canada (â‰ˆ 160 % higher in U.S.) in one older study. ğŸ§  Why does this happen? Canada uses government regulation and negotiation to constrain prices for patented drugs; the U.S. historically has fewer nationwide restrictions on drug manufacturer pricing. Brand-name drugs (patented) show the largest price gaps; generics often have smaller or even reversed differences. A study found that in 2017 the U.S. spent US $2,497 per person on health-care administrative costs, compared with US $551 per person in Canada. Thatâ€™s more than 4Ã— the Canadian per-capita amount. The source pointed out that if the U.S. reduced administrative costs to Canadian levels, it could potentially save over US $600 billion annually. Interpretation: A large chunk of U.S. spending is not directly care for patients, but overhead, billing, management, insurer profits, etc. ğŸ” Example 2: Overall Spending and Payments to Providers The U.S. spends roughly twice as much per person as â€œpeerâ€ countries (including Canada) when it comes to health care. Much of the difference comes from higher payments to hospitals, physicians, and higher prices for services â€” not necessarily more services. For example: A source reports that the U.S. was spending ~16.8% of GDP on healthcare vs Canadaâ€™s ~10.8% (in one comparison) with the U.S. per-person cost at ~US $10,948 vs Canada ~US $5,370. ğŸ” Example 3: Drug Pricing & Provider Mark-Ups While this example is more indirect, a recent report by the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) found that U.S. pharmacy benefit managers (PBMs) marked up prices of specialty generic drugs by thousands of percent between 2017-2022, leading to multi-billion-dollar gains. Higher negotiated prices, mark-ups, and less regulation in the U.S. contribute to higher profits in the supply chain. ğŸ” Why This Shows Higher Profits (and Costs) If administrative/overhead costs are dramatically higher in the U.S., that means a larger portion of healthcare dollars is going to management, insurers, bureaucratic functions, profit margins â€” rather than directly to clinical care. Higher per-person payments to hospitals and physicians suggest that U.S. providers can charge (and are paid) more for the same or similar services. Higher drug mark-ups and profit-oriented structures in the U.S. supply chain mean more of the spending ends up as profit (or margin) rather than being passed on in lower consumer/patient cost. When you combine these factors, you end up with a system where expenditures are high, yet outcomes (on many measures) are not better (and in some cases worse) compared to Canada. For instance, Canada often achieves similar or better outcomes at lower cost. âœ… Summary Yes â€” there is strong evidence that the U.S. healthcare system enables higher profits and overheads (for insurers, administrators, providers) compared to Canada, which contributes to the much higher cost burden on U.S. patients and payers.

Higher negotiated prices, mark-ups, and less regulation in the U.S. contribute to higher profits in the supply chain. ğŸ” Why This Shows Higher Profits (and Costs) If administrative/overhead costs are dramatically higher in the U.S., that means a larger portion of healthcare dollars is going to management, insurers, bureaucratic functions, profit margins â€” rather than directly to clinical care. Higher per-person payments to hospitals and physicians suggest that U.S. providers can charge (and are paid) more for the same or similar services. Higher drug mark-ups and profit-oriented structures in the U.S. supply chain mean more of the spending ends up as profit (or margin) rather than being passed on in lower consumer/patient cost. When you combine these factors, you end up with a system where expenditures are high, yet outcomes (on many measures) are not better (and in some cases worse) compared to Canada. For instance, Canada often achieves similar or better outcomes at lower cost. âœ… Summary Yes â€” there is strong evidence that the U.S. healthcare system enables higher profits and overheads (for insurers, administrators, providers) compared to Canada, which contributes to the much higher cost burden on U.S. patients and payers.

text: Lab Readiness: Positioning the Laboratory for Success in Molecular Testing This session is designed to foster collaborative problem-solving around laboratory readiness for molecular biomarker testing. Faculty composed of expert pathologists and molecular laboratory professionals will guide participants through a series of real-world case-based challenges and structured small-group discussions, focusing on issues such as test selection, validation, quality assurance, and regulatory compliance. Attendees will leave with actionable insights and peer-informed solutions they can bring back to their own practice environments. Has anyone been in persistent AFib for 6-9 months and had their SR successfully restored to normal? Mine was discovered during a routine dr visit in Sept. I was diagnosed with SVT and underwent an unsuccessful ablation in early 2020. I never had any symptoms and if not for my Apple Watch sending me alerts as my heart rate climbed to 200+,I would not have known. At the time of the ER visit for SVT the medical team stopped and restarted my heart with Adenisine. I was put on Metoprolol Tartrate which I stayed on for 5 years. I had sporadic short episodes of rapid heart rate that would go back to normal so did not think much about it when I started getting AFib alerts earlier this year on my watch. I also have a Kardia Mobile device and looking back at the history it appears I have been in persistent AFib since Jan or Feb. I had no symptoms. Fast forward to Sept 2025. I saw a new cardiologist as I now reside in a different state. She put me on Nebivilol and Eliquis and stopped Metoprolol. Iâ€™ve had a Nuclear Stress Test, a Carotid Artery Scan, an Echocardiogram, and a Sleep Study. All showed no issues. I had an unsuccessful Cardioversion last Thursday (SR was not able to be restored) and was put on Flecainide afterwards. As of this morning I am still in AFib and seeing cardiologist at noon today. My resting heart rate is around 62 and my blood pressure is good. BPM range from 50 to 85 most days. Iâ€™m guessing she will increase the dosage of Flecainide. FYI, I am 69 years old. Being overweight seems to be the only trigger I have as I do not smoke or drink alcohol or caffeine. I have made an appt with an EP on 12/23. Iâ€™m not exactly happy with my current cardiologist as her office feels like an assembly line. I am feeling out of breath from the drugs and pretty stressed out right now.

â€œGrok, how do they use fetal cell lines to make vaccines? Donâ€™t give me any opinions just facts.â€ Grok : â€œ- Fetal cell lines used in vaccine production: WI-38 (1962, female fetus, Sweden), MRC-5 (1966, male fetus, UK), HEK-293 (1973, Netherlands), PER.C6 (1995, Netherlands). - These are immortalized diploid or epithelial cell lines that replicate indefinitely in culture. - Process for viral vaccines (e.g., MMR II, Varivax, Zostavax, Vaqta, Havrix, Twinrix, Pentacel, Imovax): 1. Virus seed stock is inoculated into roller bottles or bioreactors containing WI-38 or MRC-5 cells. 2. Virus replicates inside the human cells for 3â€“14 days. 3. Culture medium containing virus is harvested. 4. Cells are separated by filtration or centrifugation. 5. Virus is purified through multiple steps: ultrafiltration, chromatography, nuclease treatment (Benzoase/DNase), and final sterile filtration. 6. Final vaccine contains live attenuated or inactivated virus plus stabilizers, no intact fetal cells. 7. Residual fetal DNA (if any) is <10 nanograms per dose (FDA limit); most vaccines have <100 picograms. - Process for recombinant protein vaccines (e.g., Hepatitis B, HPV, some COVID-19 vaccines): 1. Gene for target antigen is inserted into PER.C6 or HEK-293 cells. 2. Cells produce the protein in bioreactors. 3. Cells are lysed, protein is purified via chromatography and filtration. 4. Final product contains the purified recombinant protein. - Vaccines that use fetal cell lines in manufacturing (2025 list): - MMR II (Merck) â€“ WI-38 - ProQuad (Merck) â€“ WI-38 - Varivax (Merck) â€“ WI-38/MRC-5 - Zostavax (Merck) â€“ MRC-5 - Vaqta (Merck) â€“ MRC-5 - Havrix (GSK) â€“ MRC-5 - Twinrix (GSK) â€“ MRC-5 - Imovax Rabies (Sanofi) â€“ MRC-5 - Adenovirus oral (military) â€“ HEK-293 - Some COVID-19 vaccines (J&J, AstraZeneca) â€“ PER.C6/HEK-293 for vector production - Novavax COVID-19 â€“ no fetal cell line in final production (Sf9 insect cells) - Pfizer/BioNTech, Moderna â€“ no fetal cell line in manufacturing (mRNA synthesized chemically)

(Nov. 13, 2025) - Officers with the High Point Police Department are investigating after an argument over a turkey led to a shooting outside of a grocery store. One of the men involved was interviewed by detectives. A second person is being treated at the hospital for a gunshot wound to the arm. On November 13, 2025 at about 6:05 p.m., patrol officers responded to a reported shooting at Food Lion, located at 2705 N Main Street. When officers arrived, they found one man who had been shot in the arm. He was taken to a local hospital for treatment. According to information gathered at the scene, the situation started inside the store when a customer began to argue with an employee over a turkey. Another customer stepped in, and the two customers began to argue and fight. One customer went outside to retrieve a firearm. When he started to walk back to the store, the other customer walked out, the two men exchanged gunfire and one man was shot in the arm. The shooting happened outside of the store. Both men were at the scene when officers arrived. Detectives interviewed one of them. The injured man was taken to the hospital. This was an isolated incident. It was not an active shooter situation. This is an ongoing investigation, and this is all the information available at this time. More details will be released when appropriate.

text: The Samsung Galaxy S24 Ultra and iPhone 17 Pro Max represent two of the most powerful smartphones of 2025, catering to users seeking premium performance, cutting-edge cameras, and large, vibrant displays. While both are flagship devices, they take distinct approaches in hardware, software, and user experience. Performance & Hardware: The S24 Ultra is powered by the Snapdragon 8 Gen 3 processor, paired with 12 GB of RAM, ensuring smooth multitasking, gaming, and creative work. It can handle heavy apps, high-resolution media editing, and demanding games effortlessly. In contrast, the iPhone 17 Pro Max runs on Appleâ€™s A19 Pro chip, which leads in single-core CPU performance and optimized software integration. This makes the iPhone slightly superior for raw processing speed, gaming efficiency, and long-term software optimization. Both devices offer large storage options, with the S24 Ultra supporting up to 1 TB, and the iPhone 17 Pro Max up to 2 TB, catering to power users who store large media files or apps. Display & Design: Both phones feature large displays with high refresh rates. The S24 Ultra boasts a 6.8-inch Dynamic AMOLED 2X display with QHD+ resolution and an adaptive 1â€“120 Hz refresh rate, delivering sharp visuals, deep blacks, and excellent brightness even under sunlight. Its titanium frame adds durability and premium feel. The iPhone 17 Pro Max features a 6.9-inch Super Retina XDR OLED display with ProMotion up to 120 Hz and an Always-On display. Appleâ€™s display emphasizes color accuracy and smooth animations. Both phones are IP68-rated, providing dust and water resistance. Cameras: Camera capabilities are a key differentiator. The S24 Ultra features a quad-camera setup: a 200 MP main sensor, a 50 MP ultra-wide, a 50 MP periscope 5Ã— telephoto, and a 10 MP 3Ã— telephoto lens, along with a 12 MP front camera. Samsung emphasizes versatility, AI-assisted image enhancement, and zoom capabilities. The iPhone 17 Pro Max has a triple 48 MP camera system with wide, ultra-wide, and telephoto lenses, prioritizing computational photography, color consistency, and video recording, including ProRes formats and cinematic features. While the S24 Ultra excels in zoom and variety, the iPhone provides more consistent point-and-shoot quality and superior video tools. #fblifestylelife #SmartphoneComparison #FlagshipPhones #MobileTech2025 #AndroidVsIOS #PhoneBattle #TechReview #CameraComparison #DisplayTech

text: I just want to start by saying a huge thank you to all of you who've been speaking out, sharing your thoughts, and holding strong to what you believe. Your voice and efforts are truly making waves and looks like the district is starting to back off a bit, explaining that things like Transgender Awareness Week are just for info and not something they're pushing or celebrating in our schools. It's a positive move, don't get me wrong, but honestly, they shouldn't have put those kinds of social issues on the calendar to begin with. Topics like this are the responsibility of parents to teach their children about at home, with no place in our public school system. It seems like they're trying to ease the tension from all the feedback, but it doesn't undo the mix-up and frustration it sparked. Our kids' schools need to be all about learning, feeling safe, and coming together. I hope the board will hold the Superintendent and folks involved accountable tonight. I'll be there at tonight's school board meeting, 5:30 PM at 125 N. Boundary St. in Manning and I'd love for you to come along too. It's so important for them to see us all, to feel our shared commitment, and to know we're in this together. On that note, though, the district still hasn't touched on my other concerns about Superintendent Dr. Shawn Johnson, like those sketchy contract extensions and other lingering problems we've been talking about. We deserve real answers and accountability... no more brushing things aside. As a Christian and someone who's blessed to serve our community, I feel deeply that we have to live by God's truth. Like in Matthew 6:24: "No one can serve two masters. Either you will hate the one and love the other, or you will be devoted to the one and despise the other." We can't try to please everyone by blending worldly ideas with what the Bible teaches. God gives us that inner wisdom discernment to spot what's true to His word, and we've got to lean on that. This isn't about pushing anyone away or being unkind. The Bible tells us to love our neighbors like we love ourselves, and I believe that with all my heart. But real love doesn't mean we have to go along with or promote things that go against God's plan. Folks who say you need to buy into this stuff just to be "nice" are missing the point. We can absolutely be kind, caring, and welcoming to everyone while staying true to our faith and not endorsing what doesn't align with it. That's where genuine compassion comes from. It's about lifting each other up and safeguarding our kids and community without giving in. Let's keep lifting this up in prayer, staying connected, and pushing forward for what's best. Hope to see you tonight!

11/23/2025...I know that this is very early, especially for me, who has only decorated earlier than Thanksgiving night less than a handful of times in 71 years, but I'm still crying numerous times a day...sometimes in delirious JOY that my husband is still here, sometimes in overwhelming frustration in being SO overtired that I cannot even catch my breath, and still, occasionally, because I still watch him sleep, just to be sure that he's still BREATHING. I'm sure that you remember doing that over your newborn. I never dreamed that I'd do that over my husband, but here we are. It doesn't mean that I doubt God. That's the one thing I've never done, not ever, not once, since I committed to Him as a very young teen. But even the most glorious human beings in the world sometimes are taken before it's what we humans consider his or her time. God doesn't promise us that we'll have each other for all of our years together here on earth. He promises to be with us, no matter what happens, and I know that to be true. I can't imagine going through this without Him, but I, too, can't imagine seeing a perfect sunrise (or sunset) without Him, nor hearing a baby giggle, nor see the "light" go off in a child as they finally understand what has been being taught to them...I can't imagine one single moment of life without Him in it! His guidance, His comfort, His chiding when needed...I can't imagine life without Him. As you navigate your way through this Season of Love, I truly, with all my heart, pray that you have Him holding you, wrapping you in His love (and all that goes with His unconditional love), every single moment of every single day of your lives. We both thank you, from the bottom of our hearts, for the prayers that you've so diligently said for Ken through this journey that we've been on since June, and that ramped up SO much when he was admitted first to UMMC, then transferred to Buffalo General. He was admitted on 10/16, surgery (postponed due to him taking Eliquis in UMMC, which was the right call to treat what they had information about - AFib) was 10/27, and he was released on 10/31, a total, including partial days for admission and release, of 16 days. Your prayers during that time, and every day since he returned home, have been priceless. THANK YOU SO MUCH!!!!!!!!!! We can never repay you for your kindness, but we DO hope that you know just how much we appreciate you for your selflessness.

text: UNDERSTANDING VACCINES VS COVID VACCINES It is important to understand the difference in the mechanism of action between traditional vaccines and the Covid-19 genetic â€˜vaccinesâ€™. I have summarised and simplified the paper attached for ease of consumption: The mechanism of â€˜traditionalâ€™ vaccines consists in inoculating viruses, which have been previously inactivated (e.g. by thermal treatments), or attenuated (e.g. by multiple passages in suboptimal growth conditions). Such viruses, which lost the ability to cause acute infection, allow the immune system to recognize them as exogenous pathogens, promoting the production of specific antibodies and memory-T lymphocytes which will kill the virus. On the contrary, the genetic vaccines against COVID-19 induce human cells to produce the spike protein, producing an autoimmune reaction against all the cells that intake the genetic material and start the protein synthesis. (This is what experts call VAIDS - Vaccine Aquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome.) As concerns the Covid vaccine, it is injected into the deltoid muscle, which drains primarily to the axillary lymph nodes. Theoretically, the lipid nanoparticles (LNPs) in which the mRNA is encapsulated, should have a very restricted biodistribution; injected in the deltoid muscle which primarily drains to the axillary lymph nodes. However, a pharmacokinetic study performed by Pfizer for the Japanese regulatory agency shows that the LNPs display an off-target distribution on rodents, accumulating in organs such as the spleen, liver, pituitary gland, thyroid, ovaries and in other tissues. Similarly, the results of the European Medicines Agency (EMA) assessment reports show an off-target distribution of the LNPs used by Pfizer/BioNTech and Moderna, in the liver and other organs of rodents. In conclusion, it is essential to underline that every human cell that intakes the LNPs and translates and expresses the viral protein is inevitably recognized as a threat by the immune system and killed. There are no exceptions to this mechanism. The severity of the resulting damage and the consequences for health depend on the quantity of the cells involved, on the type of tissue and on the strength of the following autoimmune reaction.

text: Common side effects of Covishield (AstraZeneca viral vector vaccine) include pain at the injection site, headache, fatigue, fever, chills, muscle pain, and nausea, typically mild and resolving in 1-3 days per Serum Institute data. Rare serious effects involve thrombosis with thrombocytopenia syndrome (TTS) or myocarditis. For Covaxin (inactivated virus vaccine), frequent reactions are injection site tenderness, fever, headache, myalgia, and fatigue, as reported in clinical studies, with most being transient. Always review official inserts or consult healthcare providers for personalized risks.

text: Ten years ago today â€” November 1, 2015 â€” I was assigned to my very first Business Intelligence (BI) project. That moment marked the real kick-off of my career in the Data Management field. I was 27 years old, working at ITWorx, when I got the opportunity to join an on-premises BI project for Pfizer. Applied a manual MDM solution across multiple major systems. And supported reporting across the entire AFME region (Africa & Middle East). I consider myself lucky to have started my BI career when the BI was truly traditional and end-to-end â€” before heavy specialization. I got to do it all: Data Architecture, Data Modeling, ETL, Data Quality, BI & Analytics, Insights, and even a little bit of Data Science. text: ğŸš¨BREAKING: Attorney General Ken Paxton has secured a $41.5 million settlement with Pfizer and Tris Pharma for allegedly providing adulterated pharmaceutical drugs to Texas children in violation of the Texas Health Care Program Fraud Prevention Act ("THFPA"). "I will never back down from taking on the biggest corporations in the world that deceive and take advantage of Texans. Pfizer and Tris Pharma provided adulterated drugs to children for years and changed test results in order to obtain the benefit of taxpayer-funded Medicaid reimbursement," said Attorney General Paxton. "Under my watch, Big Pharma will not escape justice for lying about the effectiveness of its drugs." In November 2023, Attorney General Paxton sued Pfizer and Tris Pharma, alleging that the pharmaceutical companies had knowingly provided an ADHD medication named Quillivant XR to children on Medicaid despite the drug's pattern of failing quality control tests due to flawed manufacturing practices. The lawsuit alleged that from 2012 to 2018, Pfizer and Tris altered the drug's testing method in violation of federal and state laws to ensure Quillivant satisfied regulatory hurdles and could continue to be sold. Following Attorney General Paxton's lawsuit, Pfizer and Tris Pharma have agreed to pay $41.5 million and ensure that they follow all state and federal laws related to the manufacturing and distribution of drugs.

The memo that kicked off this whole journalistic psychodrama was authored by Michael Prescott under his former capacity as an external adviser to the BBCâ€™s Editorial Guidelines and Standards Committee. â– He is reportedly friends with Robbie Gibb, the BBC board member widely considered to be a Tory sleeper agent within the corporation. As has been extensively documented, Gibb (appointed to the board by Boris Johnson) was the director of communications for Theresa May when she was prime minister. He has described himself as a â€œproper Thatcherite Conservativeâ€. â– Aside from having questionable friendships, Prescott is a corporate lobbyist. â– Heâ€™s the managing director of Hanover Communications â€“ and his clients make for pretty grim reading. â– Chief among them is the American Pharmaceutical Group, which represents 10 of the largest U.S. pharma companies with a presence in the UK: AbbVie, Amgen, Biogen, Bristol Myers Squibb, Incyte, Gilead, J&J Innovative Medicine, Lilly, MSD, and Vertex. â– Official records show that Hanover has lobbied the Labour government on behalf of these companies over the course of the past few months. At the same time â€“ and perhaps with Prescottâ€™s help â€“ American pharma giants have been pressuring (bullying is possibly a more accurate description) the government to open up the NHS to these corporate healthcare predators. â– As reported by Politico last week, American pharma giants have threatened to leave the UK if the NHS doesnâ€™t pay more for their drugs. Eli Lilly â€“ another one of Hanoverâ€™s clients â€“ has said that it wants to see â€œsignificant and sustainableâ€ change in the NHS before restarting its investment in a biotech incubator project. This threat has been echoed by Trump, who appears to have successfully lobbied for the NHS to pay 25% more for American medicines â€“ accusing other countries of â€œfreeloadingâ€ on his countryâ€™s pharma sector. Indeed, Trump is Big Pharmaâ€™s biggest champion â€“ despite its decades-long record of fleecing, exploiting, and sometimes killing the American public. Why? Money, of course. Pharma companies donated an estimated $5 million to his re-election campaign and several million to his inauguration ceremony. Like so many other toxic, corrupt industries, theyâ€™ve bought their way into the presidentâ€™s good books. â– At the top of this list is Big Tech, which has an incestuous relationship with Trump, a man who has become a battering ram for the interests of Silicon Valley tech bros and their virulent algorithms. â– Who else is on Hanoverâ€™s client list? You guessed it â€“ Big Tech companies. Prescottâ€™s firm lobbies for Mark Zuckerbergâ€™s Meta, Jeff Bezosâ€™s Amazon, and Apple â€“ all of which have given millions of dollars to Trump in one form or another. â– â– This complicates Prescottâ€™s role in the BBC saga. It could well be argued that his firm stands to benefit from destabilising the UKâ€™s relationship with Trump, knowing that the UK government may seek to offer concessions to American industries in exchange for the president dropping his lawsuit against the BBC. â– â– We donâ€™t know these were Prescottâ€™s motives (neither he nor Hanover responded to my requests for comment), but this story is certainly not the simple tale presented by the right-wing press, of an independent, impartial observer sharing his concerns about the BBCâ€™s editorial failures. Rather, by virtue of his mega-money American clients, Michael Prescott has a lot of skin in this game â€“ a fact that should be a lot more widely understood. Hallelujah - but still no cure.

And so I sit here today, crying like a maniac because I was STUPID ENOUGH to get the vaccine Joe Biden told me to take.

Anyone else ever heard of this mystery disease?

text: BREAKTHROUGH: Study shows COVID vaccines decreased heart attacks and strokes. A major study analyzing health records from nearly 46 million adults has found that the risk of heart attacks and strokes decreased following COVID-19 vaccinations-directly challenging widespread misinformation. Published in Nature Communications, the research tracked individuals from December 2020 to January 2022 and found a 10% reduction in arterial thromboses (such as heart attacks and strokes) after the first vaccine dose. The protective effects were even stronger after second doses and boosters, with a 20% drop for Pfizer/BioNTech recipients and a 27% reduction among those who received AstraZeneca. While the study acknowledged rare risks, including myocarditis and clotting issues-mainly in the weeks immediately after vaccination-these events were extremely uncommon. In contrast, contracting COVID-19 significantly increased the risk of serious cardiovascular complications. Co-author Dr. Samantha Ip emphasized that the findings offer robust support for the safet and long-term health benefits of COVID-19 vaccines. As misinformation continues to circulate online, this study adds to a growing body of evidence showing that the vaccines don't just protect against infection-they may also reduce the risk of some of the deadliest health emergencies.

text: The space between Itâ€™s what you do for a friend. I was honored to be asked. One of the last times Jeff Prager called me after several frantic up-and-down days of at-home hospice, his blood oxygen levels are so low they cannot stabilize him. He has me on one phone, and 911 on the other phone as he unlocks his front door, Prager groans and collapses â€” dropping the phone that has me on the other end as they load him onto the gurneyâ€¦so I know heâ€™ll be taken care of.. I dial it again. An eternally cheerful recorded voice announces the message box is full. Once in the hospitalâ€™s hospice, he is put on stronger oxygen, morphine. Calls me every hour, as he feels stronger, then weaker, then frightened, then better., even hopeful!â€¦for the next 24 hours. He asks me to make some phone calls for him with instructions, and I do. Our dance of endings, and only he can hear the beat of it. Midnight on a Sunday, I text Iâ€™ll be up for a while longer, just shutting my eyes for a bit â€” but repeating that Iâ€™m right here, to let me know what he needs, to call no matter the time. At 4:38 a.m., the flip-phone I have up under my heart, rings. â€œStay with me, donâ€™t leave.â€ Of course. Then, a raspy: â€œTalk. About anything. Just talk.â€ I go over his abstract highlights on several of his key published articles from academia.edu. About how his books and essays have restructured truth-telling in the academic medical field in the last five years. Read to him from â€œThe Pfizer Papersâ€ we had previously both bought and devoured. Chapter and verse, man. Then, oh, my God: A thin voice. â€œHold my hand.â€ From a thousand miles away. Absolutely. He is closer, closing in. I remind him that, as an investigative journalist, he must find a way back to me with a complete report from the other side of what went down, his observations. â€œFind Einstein. Hell â€” find Christopher Hitchens! Thereâ€™s an interview!â€ This last part of his journey reminds how time as we imagine we know it means nothing, really. Like a tide that slides away, and you wait for it to come back and it does not. As his last horizon eases into view in this dimension, the hour is passing and his wife, Ann, who has end-stage Parkinsonâ€™s, will be moved into Pragerâ€™s room. It is this interim time â€” this space in between where a song on vinyl ends and a new one begins, that he fears being alone. That he will slip off, with no one there to hold his hand. His wife comes in finally, and I say, Jeff, hereâ€™s Ann, Iâ€™ll let you guys go. I hear her stronger voice and his weaker one: â€œNo! Stay with us. Stay.â€ Of course. Her soft voice to him, his barely audible replies. A little after 7 a.m., the steady beep-beep stops, then stretches suddenly into the steady tone, the last long goodbye. I say mine and gently hang up. -J

Read to him from â€œThe the pharmaceutical giant behind the vaccine Papersâ€ we had previously both bought and devoured. Chapter and verse, man. Then, oh, my God: A thin voice. â€œHold my hand.â€ From a thousand miles away. Absolutely. He is closer, closing in. I remind him that, as an investigative journalist, he must find a way back to me with a complete report from the other side of what went down, his observations. â€œFind Einstein. Hell â€” find Christopher Hitchens! Thereâ€™s an interview!â€ This last part of his journey reminds how time as we imagine we know it means nothing, really. Like a tide that slides away, and you wait for it to come back and it does not. As his last horizon eases into view in this dimension, the hour is passing and his wife, Ann, who has end-stage Parkinsonâ€™s, will be moved into Pragerâ€™s room. It is this interim time â€” this space in between where a song on vinyl ends and a new one begins, that he fears being alone. That he will slip off, with no one there to hold his hand. His wife comes in finally, and I say, Jeff, hereâ€™s Ann, Iâ€™ll let you guys go. I hear her stronger voice and his weaker one: â€œNo! Stay with us. Stay.â€ Of course. Her soft voice to him, his barely audible replies. A little after 7 a.m., the steady beep-beep stops, then stretches suddenly into the steady tone, the last long goodbye. I say mine and gently hang up. -J

text: European stock markets pushed higher Wednesday, helped by progress towards further U.S. stimulus, while Italian political developments and corporate earnings will also share the spotlight. At 3:50 AM ET (0850 GMT), the DAX in Germany traded 0.6% higher, the CAC 40 in France rose 0.4%, U.K.'s FTSE index climbed 0.3%, while Italyâ€™s FTSE MIB rose 2.2%. Former European Central Bank head Mario Draghi is set to meet the Italian President Sergio Mattarella later Wednesday with a view to heading up a government of national unity, something that would end the latest political crisis in Rome. This comes after party leaders failed to agree on a new coalition following the resignation of Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte last week. In corporate news, Siemens (DE:SIEGn) stock rose 2.1% after the German manufacturing conglomerate lifted its full-year guidance, citing faster-than-expected recoveries in China and Germany following the Covid-19 downturn. Banco Santander (MC:SAN) stock rose 2.6% after the Spanish bank declared a cash dividend for 2020 at the maximum level allowed in accordance with the limits set by the European Central Bank, despite recording its first ever annual loss ever. Novo Nordisk A/S (NYSE:NVO) stock added 3.9% after the diabetes drug maker gave upbeat sales and profit forecasts for 2021, while Swedish truckmaker Volvo (ST:VOLVb) stock rose 0.3% after raising its forecasts for some of its main markets and rolling out a hefty shareholder payout. On Tuesday, the U.S. Senate began debating a budget resolution for 2021, the first step towards passing a $1.9 trillion stimulus package proposed by President Joe Biden without Republican support. Additionally, the roll-out of vaccines in many countries is slowly gathering pace: the U.K. has now inoculated 10 million of its population, although health authorities remain concerned by the spread of new variants of the Covid-19 virus. AstraZeneca (LON:AZN) has agreed to deliver nine million more doses of its vaccine to the European Union in the first quarter of this year, a region which has been slow on the inoculation uptake. Oil prices edged higher, still around the highest levels in a year after an unexpected fall in U.S. crude oil supply. The American Petroleum Institute reported late Tuesday crude inventories fell by 4.3 million barrels last week, compared with expectations for a small build. Data from the U.S. Energy Information Administration is due later in the day. U.S. crude futures traded 0.6% higher at $55.08 a barrel, after hitting a one-year high of $55.26 on Tuesday. The international benchmark Brent contract rose 0.1% to $57.88, after earlier climbing to $58.05, its highest in more than 11 months. Elsewhere, gold futures rose 0.3% to $1,838.30/oz, while EUR/USD traded 0.1% lower at 1.2035.

text: The Whittington brothers put two Porsche 935 chassis on the tarmac at Watkins Glen in 1979. The first was chassis 77A #930 890 0023, purchased directly by the brothers through VW America. This chassis was the winner that day, under the Le Mans winning drive, including the two brothers, Don and Bill, alongside the genius Klaus Ludwig. The second chassis is a 1979 #930 990 0028, also purchased by the brothers that same year along with #930 990 0026. This chassis was also driven that day by Brian Redman. There were 43 international teams that started the race that Sunday, July 7. The Whittingtons won the race four laps ahead of Rolf Stommelen, Dick Barbour and Paul Newman. They also won the 6 Hours of Riverside at Le Mans and the 6 Hours of Daytona with Dennis Shaw driving for Amos N. Johnson. text: Michael Kenneth Williams (November 22, 1966 â€“ September 6, 2021) was an American actor. He played Omar Little on the HBO drama series The Wire from 2002 to 2008 and Albert "Chalky" White on the HBO series Boardwalk Empire from 2010 to 2014. He earned Primetime Emmy Award nominations for his performances in the HBO television biopic Bessie (2015), the Netflix drama series When They See Us (2019), and the HBO series The Night Of (2016) and Lovecraft Country (2020). He had a recurring role in the sitcom Community from 2011 to 2012. He also had supporting roles in a number of films including Gone Baby Gone (2006), The Road (2009), 12 Years a Slave (2013), Inherent Vice (2014), and Motherless Brooklyn (2019). Williams was born in Brooklyn, New York City, the son of a Bahamian mother from Nassau and Booker T. Williams, an American, from Greeleyville, South Carolina, where his African-American family has deep roots. Williams was raised in the Vanderveer Projects in East Flatbush, Brooklyn, and attended George Westinghouse Career and Technical Education High School. According to a DNA analysis, he was descended partly from the Mende people of Sierra Leone. After getting into trouble as a youth, he enrolled at the National Black Theatre in New York City. Williams worked for Pfizer pharmaceuticals as a temp. However, inspired by Janet Jackson's Rhythm Nation 1814, he left school and quit his job, against the wishes of his family, to pursue a career as a dancer. During a year in which he was intermittently homeless, Williams visited record labels and dance studios looking for work. He got a job as a background dancer with singer Kym Sims, which led to more work appearing as a dancer in music videos and on tours with artists such as George Michael and Madonna, as well as some modeling work. He also choreographed Crystal Waters' 1994 single "100% Pure Love". Williams had a large facial scar he received in a bar fight on Jamaica Avenue, New York City, on his 25th birthday, when he was slashed with a razor blade. The scar became his signature feature, and resulted in offers to perform as a thug in music videos, and modeling opportunities with noted photographers like David LaChapelle. One of his first acting roles was alongside Tupac Shakur as High Top, the brother and henchman to Shakur's drug kingpin Tank, in the 1996 film Bullet. Shakur reportedly decided on Williams for the role after spotting a polaroid photograph of him in a production studio. Williams also served as the American Civil Liberties Union celebrity ambassador to the Campaign for Smart Justice. Williams' portrayals of openly gay characters was deemed to be revolutionary. Williams gained recognition as an actor for his portrayal of Omar Little in The Wire, which began filming in 2002. The character was based on Donnie Andrews along with other crime figures in Baltimore. Williams received the part after a single audition, at the encouragement of writer Ed Burns. He was told that the character was slated to appear in just seven episodes and expected him to be killed by the end of the first season. However, creator David Simon stated that they always planned to keep the character as part of the continuing ensemble should the show be renewed beyond one season. Omar was praised for his uniqueness in the stale landscape of TV crime dramas and for the wit and humor that Williams brings to the portrayal. Omar has been named as one of the first season's richest characters, a Robin Hood of Baltimore's west side projects. The Baltimore City Paper named the character one of their top ten reasons not to cancel the show and called him "arguably the show's single greatest achievement". In 2007, he was nominated for an NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actor in a Drama Series for his role as Omar. Williams pursued the role because he was intrigued by Omar's contradictory nature. He felt Omar's popularity stemmed from his honesty, lack of materialism, individuality and his adherence to his strict code. He felt that the role has been a breakthrough in terms of bringing attention to him and getting further roles. Williams received both positive and negative reactions to Omar's homosexuality and felt that he was successful in challenging attitudes and provoking discussion with the role. In 2008, then-U.S. Senator Barack Obama cited The Wire as his favorite television show, and called Omar his favorite character. About Omar, Obama said, "That's not an endorsement. He's not my favorite person, but he's a fascinating character ... he's the toughest, baddest guy on the show." During his portrayal of Omar Little, Williams went by his character's name and developed a habit of smoking cannabis and an addiction to cocaine in 2004. Williams lived part-time in Newark, New Jersey using drugs, but sought help from a ministry in neighboring Irvington, which he credited for helping him during the production. Williams was found dead in his Williamsburg, Brooklyn apartment by his nephew on September 6, 2021. On September 24, 2021, the NYC Office of Chief Medical Examiner confirmed that Williams died of a fatal combination of fentanyl, p-fluorofentanyl, heroin and cocaine, and ruled the death as an accidental overdose. His private funeral was held at St. Stephen's Episcopal Cathedral in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania where his mother lives.

So I went got my eyes tested, and the optician saw something in my left eye, and referred me to the eye hospital at QA. The eye hospital said they wanted me to have a MRI which I had in January. After this I would ask my doctor numerous times what was the results of my MRI. His reply was if we donâ€™t hear from them, then thatâ€™s usually a good sign. Well it turns out that scan in January actually showed that I had had a stroke caused by a blood clot to my left optical region of my brain. He was extremely apologetic and could not understand why this has not been brought to his attention so that we could treat the problem back then .
