text: Bell: The point here is that, whatever new data is coming out on Covid vaccines, the public was systematically misled, misinformed, and lied to by our public health agencies. This is not controversial â€“ they simply were. We can wonder at the lack of interest in the excess deaths in the vaccinated group over the unvaccinated in the 6-month Pfizer trial published in 2021, and the lack of any detectable benefit on mortality in the equivalent Moderna trial. We can wonder at the secrecy around the commitment of hundreds of billions of public funds in pre-purchase commitments, sometimes negotiated by text message, and how the people who did this are still in power. We can really wonder why there is so little solid data on overall mortality and disability of vaccinated versus unvaccinated people, when this is such an obvious thing for our governments to check. Human biology is complex and variable â€“ lots of people (clearly) had plenty of injections and are (and almost certainly will be) fine. Lots of others probably will not be so fine. This is why, back in the days of medical ethics, we were supposed to be informed and given a choice. We really should wonder why that changed, and why doctors agreed to go along with it (such things have happened before).

The opioid crisis in the United States, which has resulted in hundreds of thousands of overdose deaths, has been heavily linked to aggressive marketing and over-prescription of opioids by certain pharmaceutical companies. While numerous corporations (such as Johnson & Johnson, Teva, and Endo) have faced lawsuits and settlements for their roles in fueling addiction through misleading promotion and supply chain practices, the most prominent is the Sackler family and their control of Purdue Pharma.

Purdue aggressively promoted OxyContin to physicians, downplaying its addictive potential and encouraging high-dose, long-term prescriptions. Internal documents revealed deceptive tactics, including funding biased research and paying doctors kickbacks. This contributed to a surge in prescriptionsâ€”from about 670,000 in 1997 to over 15 million by 2002â€”driving widespread addiction and the broader opioid epidemic.

The family reaped billions in dividends from OxyContin sales, which peaked at over $3 billion annually. Estimates suggest they extracted at least $10-13 billion from Purdue between 2008 and 2019 alone, much of it transferred offshore amid growing scrutiny.

A few cases involve founders or executives:
- John Kapoor and Insys Therapeutics: Kapoor, the founder (not a multi-generational family operation), led aggressive promotion of Subsys (a fentanyl spray), including bribing doctors for prescriptions. Insys paid $225 million in settlements, and Kapoor was convicted of racketeering in 2019, serving prison time. Profits from these tactics contributed to over-prescription of fentanyl products.

Broader industry accountability includes multi-billion-dollar settlements from firms like Johnson & Johnson ($5 billion national settlement) for supplying raw opioid ingredients and deceptive marketing.

BMS talk for TYs On Tuesday 21st October 2025, we welcomed representatives from Bristol Myers Squibb (BMS) Cruiserath Biologics to speak to TYs - Lorraine Kelly and Donal Monaghan. Bristol Myers Squibb is a global biopharmaceutical company whose mission is to discover, develop and deliver innovative medicines that help patients prevail over serious diseases. The visitors spoke to TYs about the career opportunities across multiple functions, including Biologics Manufacturing, External Manufacturing and Commercial. TYs learned that BMS first began operations in Ireland in 1964 with an Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient Plant (API) in Swords, County Dublin. The current BMS operations in Ireland include a newly constructed state-of-the-art biologics drug-substance manufacturing facility in Cruiserath, Dublin 15 and External Manufacturing divisions in Blanchardstown, Dublin 15 and Shannon, Co. Clare. BMS Ireland employs approximately 650 people. The TYs also learned about the pathways each of the 2 employees went on since college, which was really interesting. The company collaborates with second level institutions, particularly those with a core focus on STEM subjects. Their TY programme is an exciting week-long programme of activity for TY students with an interest in learning more about a career in science, engineering and the pharmaceutical sector in Ireland. A number of TYs have applied for this programme so hopefully a student will get a place. BMS also offer an Apprenticeship Programme designed to offer hands on experience and a robust foundation for individuals eager to embark on a career in the pharmaceutical industry. This is done through structured education, formal training and learning in the workplace. It takes 2 years to complete the Level 6 qualification, with an optional third year for those pursuing a Level 7 qualification. Thanks to Lorraine and Donal for visiting ACS. We really appreciate your time.

Know Your Biomarker is an awareness, education, and advocacy campaign promoting global access to colorectal cancer biomarker testing. While they compete in the same premium space, each takes a different approach to photography, display, and user experience, making them suited to different types of users. The Pixel 10 Pro XL features a 6.8-inch OLED display with a 120 Hz refresh rate and high peak brightness, delivering sharp visuals and smooth scrolling. Its rear camera system includes a 50 MP main sensor, a 48 MP ultra-wide lens, and a 48 MP telephoto lens with 5Ã— optical zoom. This combination, paired with Googleâ€™s renowned computational photography, produces consistent, balanced images with excellent dynamic range. Samsung Galaxy S26 Ultra Overview The Galaxy S26 Ultra offers a 6.9-inch Dynamic AMOLED QHD+ display with 120 Hz refresh rate and exceptional brightness and contrast, ideal for media consumption and detailed photo/video review. Its rear quad-camera system is highly versatile: a 200 MP main lens, 50 MP ultra-wide, and two telephoto lenses (3Ã— and 5Ã— optical zoom). This setup allows for wide-angle, zoomed, and detailed shots, providing unmatched flexibility for photography enthusiasts. While the front camera is 12 MP, slightly lower than the Pixel, it is sufficient for standard selfies and video calls. Under the hood, the S26 Ultra runs on the Snapdragon 8 Elite Gen 5, offering top-tier performance for gaming, content creation, and heavy multitasking. Its 5,000 mAh battery is slightly smaller than the Pixelâ€™s but optimized for balanced usage.

text: Do I really need to tell you we're winning today? Come now - it's the Boks' green hydra gargling French tears in Turin, facing down an Azzurri no longer under the radar. We've got the scalps, the depth dialed deep, and the skulls geared to jam into the cogs. No sidestepping blood if glory's the game. No, you don't need me to spell it; you know it bone-deep like a Bok tackle - what your skeleton feels like inside your flesh - that innate certainty perfumed with the thrill of the unfolding. To some, it'll always look like arrogance. But is it not the simple math of momentum meeting the momentary, the inevitable echo from events? If I'm going on tangent, it's because Italy believes this is their shot - the outsiders' dream. And they're right. It's a dream. Everyone will want to put their hand up today, stain the jersey with their blood. Repeat lineups are recipes for rust, sayeth Rassie. Complacency embarrassed us earlier this year against Australia at Ellis Park, but truth be told, the cracks were hairline against Italy - despite nulling them with 14 men last. We're making amends well when required this year, and with grievances, the minds of the fresh charges look well framed. Add to this a bench that chews souls, and Italy's dream sours quick. We won't be taking them easy, but take them we will, one way or another. The wordless wink this week: Do we really need adversity to thrive? Against Italy no less... It's a mythological trap that could one day undo us. Personnel's not the main puzzle - the mind's contingencies win this war. Do we need the brink to bite? Boss from boot to buzzer, no flirt with the fall? Warp-spasm our weird wingman, or bad Bok habit? Must we dip to better soar? Pondering that's pure luxury. That's how far we've come. Prediction: Boks 49-17. Forza? Nah - voetsek, victory! #Springboks #Bokke #ItalyVsBoks #RassieRiddle #Rugby #TurinTest #WarpSpasm #WhatsNotToLove #VoetsekVictory

text: To get all my FB friends filled in on what my last month was likeâ€¦ here we go !!! On October 17th late Friday my right leg including my foot swelled dramatically. I wasnâ€™tâ€™ sure what it was & hoped it would pass, and it didnâ€™t so Monday I called 911 and was rushed to ER at Lutheran General Hospital where I was diagnosed with a major +DVT (Deep Venous Thrombosis) which in lay terms is a blood clot. I was immediately put on blood thinners (LMW-Heparin ie. Lovenox). Ultra sound & CT scans revealed a clot starting below my knee in my calf, leading up my thigh all the way into my inferior vena cava, along with a few pulmonary embolisms (thankfully non-life threatening due to their placement). Surgery was scheduled first for Wednesday the 22nd but finally happened Thursday the 23rd. I basically had a human RotoRouter performed where one orthoscopic went in behind my right knee & a second came in from up high in the top of my neck. Both would meet in the middle and the surgeon said the clot they pulled out was over 3 ft long. Also the neck probe went over to my left leg to remove some residual clotting I had there as well.. (I had been plagued with some edema in my feet off and on, for quite a while, thinking it was water retention not knowing it was actually clots). I was released from the hospital on Wednesday afternoon the 29th and have been on home rehab since. I get around with a walker due to the pain & swelling still present in my right leg which is slowly going away. I am thankful for all the prayers & support from everyone & my close friends (you know who you are) have been fantastic with my home support. I will be on blood thinners (DOACs,direst oral.. Eliquis) for at least several months. I have another CT scan scheduled for Nov. 22nd to see if all clotting has cleared. Iâ€™m here, I survived, by the grace of God & again I am grateful for all the DRâ€™s, Nurses NAâ€™s and all around me. Iâ€™m getting home PT and a nurse visiting a few times a week so Iâ€™m on the mend. And yes, Iâ€™m back to work (at home which is normal) as best I can handle. So there you have it !!

Healthcare is broken Healthcare in costs in America is a tragedy ğŸ¤¬ğŸ¤¬ğŸ¤¬ğŸ¤¬ğŸ¤¬ A U.S. government study found that in 2022, U.S. drug prices were on average ~229 % of Canadian prices (i.e., Canadian prices were about 44 % of what Americans paid) for the same drugs. Another review noted that for brand-name drugs, U.S. prices can be ~3 to 4 times higher than in Canada (or higher, depending on the specific drug). For example: Eliquis (a blood thinner) costs in the U.S. ~$1,668 for 180 tablets, while in Canada the lowest listed price was ~$370. Jardiance (for diabetes) cost ~$1,845 in the U.S. for 90 tablets versus ~$290 in Canada. An analysis found that Rinvoq (for Crohnâ€™s/ulcerative colitis) is ~$11,915 in the U.S. vs ~$1,749.95 in Canada â€” roughly 7Ã— the Canadian price. âš ï¸ Examples of drugs with large U.S.â€“Canada price gaps Eliquis: ~4.5Ã— higher in the U.S. vs Canada. Jardiance: ~6Ã—+ higher in the U.S. vs Canada. Rinvoq: ~7Ã— higher. In a broader list: Latuda (an antipsychotic) 90 tablets cost ~$4,628 in U.S., ~$520 in Canada (~89 % cheaper in Canada). Synthroid (for hypothyroidism) cost ~$114 in U.S. vs ~$44 in Canada (â‰ˆ 160 % higher in U.S.) in one older study. ğŸ§  Why does this happen? Canada uses government regulation and negotiation to constrain prices for patented drugs; the U.S. historically has fewer nationwide restrictions on drug manufacturer pricing. Brand-name drugs (patented) show the largest price gaps; generics often have smaller or even reversed differences. A study found that in 2017 the U.S. spent US $2,497 per person on health-care administrative costs, compared with US $551 per person in Canada. Thatâ€™s more than 4Ã— the Canadian per-capita amount. The source pointed out that if the U.S. reduced administrative costs to Canadian levels, it could potentially save over US $600 billion annually. Interpretation: A large chunk of U.S. spending is not directly care for patients, but overhead, billing, management, insurer profits, etc. ğŸ” Example 2: Overall Spending and Payments to Providers The U.S. spends roughly twice as much per person as â€œpeerâ€ countries (including Canada) when it comes to health care. Much of the difference comes from higher payments to hospitals, physicians, and higher prices for services â€” not necessarily more services. For example: A source reports that the U.S. was spending ~16.8% of GDP on healthcare vs Canadaâ€™s ~10.8% (in one comparison) with the U.S. per-person cost at ~US $10,948 vs Canada ~US $5,370. ğŸ” Example 3: Drug Pricing & Provider Mark-Ups While this example is more indirect, a recent report by the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) found that U.S. pharmacy benefit managers (PBMs) marked up prices of specialty generic drugs by thousands of percent between 2017-2022, leading to multi-billion-dollar gains. Higher negotiated prices, mark-ups, and less regulation in the U.S. contribute to higher profits in the supply chain. ğŸ” Why This Shows Higher Profits (and Costs) If administrative/overhead costs are dramatically higher in the U.S., that means a larger portion of healthcare dollars is going to management, insurers, bureaucratic functions, profit margins â€” rather than directly to clinical care. Higher per-person payments to hospitals and physicians suggest that U.S. providers can charge (and are paid) more for the same or similar services. Higher drug mark-ups and profit-oriented structures in the U.S. supply chain mean more of the spending ends up as profit (or margin) rather than being passed on in lower consumer/patient cost. When you combine these factors, you end up with a system where expenditures are high, yet outcomes (on many measures) are not better (and in some cases worse) compared to Canada. For instance, Canada often achieves similar or better outcomes at lower cost. âœ… Summary Yes â€” there is strong evidence that the U.S. healthcare system enables higher profits and overheads (for insurers, administrators, providers) compared to Canada, which contributes to the much higher cost burden on U.S. patients and payers.

text: Have a question. Has anyone that is taking daily blood thinners ever gotten another Pulmonary Embolism in the lungs while on the blood thinners? This is why I'm asking. My husband had Bilateral Pulmonary Embolisms in Feb. of this year. He has taken blood thinners (Eliquis) every day since then. At different dr. appointments during the year he has asked if it is possible to get more clots while on blood thinners and each dr. has said No, it is not possible. A month a go he had major back surgery and about a week a go, his left calf has been aching. (he was off his Eliquis a few days before and after his surgery per the doctors orders) When he lays on his back to sleep, the pressure from the mattress makes his calf ache and he says it hurts if he pushes on it. There is no redness, no hard bump in his calf. He says his foot and calf feel a little tight (like it is swollen) I have looked at his leg and to me it does not look swollen, but he said his skin feels tight. He has other medical problem, and has had at different times, swollen feet and ankles, so he knows that feeling. Anyway, he doesn't know if the achiness in his calf is from the back surgery and his body trying to heal or possibly another clot has formed. We have googled if you can still get a blood clot while take blood thinners, it says it is NOT common but it can happen. He has a doctor appointment soon to have it checked but wanted to know if anyone here on this group has had a re-occurring blood clot while on blood thinners. Thanks in advance for sharing your experience that you may have had. Sometimes we both feel we are over thinking things .... but afraid if we ignore something.... then that's when something might happen again.

text: Grrrrr president trump!! Nonprofit hospitals and health clinics are alarmed about a change that's coming to federal drug purchasing discounts next year. They'll have to pay up front and then get rebates â€” rather than direct price cuts â€” in a pilot with eight pharmaceutical companies. Why it matters: The new system, greenlit by the Trump administration, is a win for drugmakers, and it could be a big hassle for providers. Under the test, which starts in January, providers will pay full price for drugs they currently get at a steep discount. They'll get reimbursed the difference after the drugmaker determines they qualify for the lower price under the 340B program, which allows nonprofit safety net providers to access lower-cost outpatient drugs. What they're saying: "Many hospitals are concerned about cash flow around this," Maureen Testoni, CEO of the provider trade group 340B Health, said on a recent call with reporters. Providers will have to hire new staff to submit data to get the rebates, or at least shift employee responsibilities around, she said. She noted that the change comes as providers prepare for cuts to Medicaid reimbursement and other likely changes that could reduce their Medicare payments. Where it stands: The Health Resources and Services Administration last week approved 340B rebate programs for nine popular drugs, including Bristol Myers Squibb's blood thinner Eliquis and Janssen's Stelara and Xarelto. The pilot will run for at least one year to test whether rebates work for 340B discounts, HHS said in July when it first announced the idea. PhRMA sees the rebate pilot as a step toward more transparency and accountability in the 340B program, senior director of public affairs Molly Jenkins said in a statement. The administration should go further and allow rebates across all 340B-covered outpatient drugs, Jenkins added. Several pharmaceutical companies have tried to implement their own rebate systems in recent years, arguing they guard against providers getting duplicate discounts or diverting 340B drugs to ineligible patients. Courts have so far blocked them from doing so without HHS approval. Yes, but: The nonprofit health system Advocate Health says the savings from direct discounts allow it to invest $6 billion annually into free clinics, charity care and community-based programs. "A shift to a rebate model, as opposed to the current discount model, would undercut our ability to continue this level of care," the health system's leaders wrote in a comment letter to HHS earlier this year. The rebate model "is a clear case of the fox guarding the hen house," Jennifer DeCubellis, CEO of America's Essential Hospitals, said in a statement, adding that "drug manufacturers are the only winners" of the program. The other side: HHS maintains that the pilot is a limited, data-driven effort to improve 340B, press secretary Emily Hilliard told Axios via email. HHS is undertaking the project to "better understand the merits and shortcomings of the rebate model from the perspective of affected stakeholders," she wrote.

With tears of gratitude, I want to formally announce the arrival of Ramon to the United States. I am literally indebted with my life to this lady who had faith in us to co-sponsor him. You are our hero, my lifeline, our hope Joy Liebfreund Seagraves. Muchisimas gracias de mi corazon! I have been getting treatment at The OSU James Cancer Center for follicular lymphoma (FL) cancer since 2020. I have failed three types of chemo and my FL has transformed into aggressive diffuse large b cell lymphoma (DLBCL). Cancer has progressed to my lungs. It was not possible for me to start with Breyanzi CAR-T treatment unless I could guarantee to my hematologist that I had someone with me 24/7 for a minimum of one month (given any unforeseen circumstances). This procedure called "apheresis" begins on December 5th with extracting my t-cells (via a pic line) for submission to Bristol Meyers Squibb (BMS) for genetic modification in their laboratory. This is to make a man-made protein on the surface of the cell called chimeric antigen receptor (CAR). These receptors are designed to bind the surface of the cancer cells, which lets the modified T cells attack them like Pacman. The CAR-T cells fight the cancer and help protect against the return of cancer. The CAR-T cells are multiplied, frozen and sent back to the hospital. During this process I will continue to have cycles of chemo to get rid of the remaining cancerous T cells. After the T-Cells are received from BMS, I will receive them as an outpatient. This process is not without serious risks of Tumor Lysis Syndrome (TLS), Cytokine Release Syndrome (CRS), neurological toxicity, risks of infection and/or other side effects, hence, the reason for having someone by my side 24/7. We must live within 30 minutes of the clinic in the event of a crisis. The James will provide our hotel stay in Columbus. The risks are very frightening but it is our hope that CAR-T will allow me more time with Ramon as there is no cure for blood cancer. I appreciate all the love, support and prayers that you all have provided. Please don't stop now as this new chapter will be a delicate process. Pray with us that there will be no or few complications and limited stress for Ramon as my caretaker. We appreciate your support in my previous post "We Got This" to help with expenses and needs while in Columbus without cooking facilities and in our journey in the road ahead. I would be remiss not to acknowledge the help of Ellen, immigration case manager, in Senator Bernie Moreno's office. Her patience and perseverance in communicating with me and the US Embassy in Santo Domingo enabled Ramon to receive an expedited family visa (though we had been in this process for 6 disappointing years). Also, with the help of letters and the pathology report from my doctor, Ramon is with me. He is 100% legal in the US with a green card and social security card to work when that time comes. For now, our focus is on my health. That will be a job in itself! LOL! To this end, if it weren't for Joy's sponsorship of Ramon, my hope of an extended life would not be possible. Ohh, we give our gratitude to all who have donated winter clothes to Ramon. He arrived with a small luggage full of summer clothes. He is now prepared for winter, thanks to many. Our first snowfall he was like a little kid running from window to window to see the snow and calling all his family on Messenger live chat to show them the white stuff. It brought me so much happiness! So much to be thankful for! Give Thanks To Life and Great Friends! We Got This! We love you, Joy!

AI Overview +6 Understanding CAR-T cell therapy for cancer: Mayo Clinic ... CAR T-cell therapy is a type of immunotherapy that genetically engineers a patient's own T cells to recognize and attack cancer cells. The process involves collecting a patient's T cells, modifying them in a lab to express a chimeric antigen receptor (CAR), growing them, and then infusing them back into the patient to target and kill cancer cells. This treatment has been effective against certain blood cancers, like lymphoma and leukemia, even when other treatments have failed. How it works Collection: A patient's T cells are collected from their blood. Modification: The T cells are genetically engineered in a lab to create CAR T cells. These cells are equipped with a chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) that helps them identify and bind to a specific protein on the surface of cancer cells. Expansion: The CAR T cells are grown in large numbers in the lab. Infusion: The CAR T cells are infused back into the patient's bloodstream. Attack: The CAR T cells find and destroy the cancer cells. What it treats CAR T-cell therapy is used to treat certain types of cancer, including some forms of leukemia, lymphoma, and multiple myeloma. Important considerations It is a form of cell-based gene therapy. Some patients may experience significant side effects, such as confusion, seizures, or brain swelling, which require close monitoring. It is not effective for all patients, and some may experience a relapse after the treatment. text: Prof Uzma Firdaus Appointed Chairperson of AMUâ€™s Department of Paediatrics ALIGARH, November 24: Prof Uzma Firdaus of the Department of Paediatrics, Jawaharlal Nehru Medical College, Aligarh Muslim University, has been appointed Chairperson of the department for a three-year term beginning November 24. An accomplished clinician and academician, Prof Firdaus brings 18 years of teaching experience to the role. Her areas of specialisation include neonatology and developmental paediatrics. Prof Firdaus serves as the Nodal Officer for the District Early Intervention Centre and the Centre of Excellence established under the Rashtriya Bal SwasthyaKaryakram (RBSK), National Health Mission. She has also completed a major multicentric research project on severe pneumonia in children under the IndiaCLEN and MCH STAR initiative. Her academic profile includes 40 research publications in national and international journals, 25 presented papers, three published books, and extensive involvement in postgraduate thesis supervision. She has received several prestigious recognitions, including the Prof R.S. Dayal Gold Medal in Neonatology, the Dr Hadi Hasan Memorial Medal, and the Pfizer Award, along with multiple university medals and distinctions. Prof Firdaus is trained in Paediatric Advanced Life Support (PALS) and Neonatal Advanced Life Support (NALS) and is a certified trainer for the NavjaatShishu Suraksha Karyakram (NSSK). Public Relations Office Aligarh Muslim University

text: Join us this Sunday, November 9th at 3pm ET for a special episode of The Doctor Is In. We will be talking to Paris Johnson who overseas clinical trial site engagement for AstraZeneca. AstraZeneca is committed to recruiting Black women in their clinical trials and we are ecstatic to support them in this critical work. We are working with them to provide our TOUCH Care, our 24/7 nurse navigation for patients in the trial. This clinical trial, TROPION-Breast 05, is specifically designed for metastatic patients with PD-L1 positive Triple Negative Breast Cancer as a first-line treatment (meaning this is your first treatment for metastatic TNBC). This trial combines DATROWAY with an immunotherapy drug called Durvalumab (a drug similar to Keytruda). Science is constantly advancing and there are currently limited options for TNBC. The goal of this trial is to see if combining the new targeted drug, DATROWAY, with Durvalumab works more effectively than and/or provides another treatment option versus the current standard treatment (Chemotherapy + Keytruda) for metastatic patients with PD-L1 positive TNBC. if this is confusing to you, just watch this episode and we will put a hug around this science for you. The really good news here is that we have another much-needed treatment option for Triple Negative Breast Cancer. Tune in on Sunday, November 9th at 3pmET, Facebook.com/BlackDoctor.org. #WhenWeTrial #clinicaltrials #clinicalresearch #tnbc #tnbcwarrior Join Us! text: One more reason not to take it...they just keep coming, don't they? News News News @NewsNew97351204 Breaking News Scientists discover Pfizer COVID jab linked to major eye damage If you have had a similar reaction to Pfizer's COVID-19 vaccine, email chris.melore@dailymail.com with your story Scientists have discovered that Pfizer's COVID-19 vaccine may increase the risk of eye damage, leading to vision loss. The new study specifically examined how the vaccine affected patients' corneas, the clear front part of the eye that allows light to enter. In 64 people, scientists in Turkey measured changes in the cornea's inner layer, called the endothelium, before taking the first Pfizer dose and two months after receiving the second. Results revealed that taking both doses of the vaccine led to thicker corneas, fewer endothelial cells in the eye and more variation in size of these specialized cells that form the endothelium. In the short term, these changes suggest the Pfizer vaccine may temporarily weaken the endothelium, even though patients didn't suffer clear vision problems during the study. For people with healthy eyes, these small changes likely won't affect vision right away. However, if scientists find that these changes last for years, they could lead to corneal swelling or blurry vision, especially in those with pre-existing eye problems or people who have had a cornea transplant. A thicker cornea and reduced cell density could contribute to eye conditions like corneal edema, bullous keratopathy, or corneal decompensation, which can all cause permanent vision loss in severe cases, especially if left untreated. Jul 18, 2025

text: A BMS most commonly refers to a Building Management System (also called Building Automation System or BAS). Here's a clear overview: ### What is a BMS? A Building Management System is an integrated computer-based control system installed in buildings that monitors and controls the buildingâ€™s mechanical and electrical equipment such as: - HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning) - Lighting - Power systems - Fire systems - Security systems (access control, CCTV) - Lifts/elevators - Water supply and plumbing - Energy metering ### Main Functions of a BMS 1. Centralized Control â€“ Operators can monitor and control all systems from a single interface (usually a software dashboard). 2. Energy Management â€“ Optimizes energy use (e.g., turns off lights/HVAC in unoccupied areas, adjusts temperature setpoints). 3. Alarm Management â€“ Detects faults (e.g., pump failure, high room temperature) and alerts operators. 4. Data Logging & Trending â€“ Records historical data for analysis and reporting. 5. Scheduling â€“ Automates routines (e.g., office lights on at 7 AM, off at 7 PM). 6. Remote Access â€“ Many modern BMS allow control via web or mobile apps. ### Common BMS Protocols - BACnet (most widely used open protocol) - Modbus - LonWorks - KNX - DALI (for lighting) - OPC ### Major BMS Manufacturers/Brands - Siemens (Desigo) - Honeywell (EBI, ComfortPoint) - Schneider Electric (EcoStruxure, Andover Continuum, TAC) - Johnson Controls (Metasys) - Tridium (Niagara Framework â€“ integrator platform) - Distech Controls - Trend Controls - Delta Controls - Automated Logic (WebCTRL) ### Other Meanings of BMS (context-dependent) - Battery Management System â€“ Used in electric vehicles and battery storage (monitors cell voltage, temperature, state of charge, etc.). - Business Management System â€“ General term for integrated business software. - Bristol-Myers Squibb â€“ Pharmaceutical company (stock ticker BMS). - Burner Management System â€“ Safety system for industrial boilers/furnaces. If youâ€™re asking about a specific type (e.g., building BMS, EV battery BMS) or need details about integration, programming, or a particular brand, let me know and I can go deeper!

text: WASHINGTON (AP) - President Donald Trump unveiled a deal Thursday with drugmakers Eli Lilly and Novo Nordisk to expand coverage and reduce prices for their popular obesity treatments Zepbound and Wegovy. The drugs are part of a new generation of obesity medications known as GLP-1 receptor agonists that have soared in popularity in recent years. But access to the drugs has been a consistent problem for patients because of their cost - around $500 a month for higher doses - and insurance coverage has been spotty. Coverage of the drugs for obesity will expand to Medicare patients starting next year, according to the administration, which said some lower prices also will be phased in for patients without coverage. Starting doses of new, pill versions of the treatments also will cost $149 a month if they are approved. Thursdays announcement is the latest attempt by the Trump administration to rein in soaring drug prices in its efforts to address cost-of-living concerns among voters. Drugmakers Pfizer and AstraZeneca recently agreed to lower the cost of prescription drugs for Medicaid after an executive order in May set a deadline for drugmakers to electively lower prices or face new limits on what the government will pay. As with the other deals, its not clear how much the price drop will be felt by consumers. Drug prices can vary based on the competition for treatments and insurance coverage. Obesity drugs have become increasingly popular, but are costly The obesity drugs work by targeting hormones in the gut and brain that affect appetite and feelings of fullness. In clinical trials, they helped people shed between 15%% and 22%% of their body weight -- up to 50 pounds or more in many cases. Patients taking these drugs usually start on smaller doses and then work up to larger amounts, depending on their needs. Because of obesity being considered a chronic disease, they need to take the treatment indefinitely or risk regaining weight, experts say. The fast-growing treatments have proven especially lucrative for drugmakers Eli Lilly and Co. and Novo Nordisk. Lilly said recently that sa #wsbtv #crimewatchatlanta les of Zepbound have tripled so far this year to more than $9 billion. But for many Americans, their cost has made them out of reach. Medicare, the federally funded coverage program mainly for people ages 65 and over, hasnt covered the treatments for obesity. President Donald Trumps predecessor, Joe Biden, proposed a rule last November that would have changed that. But the Trump administration nixed it last spring. Few state and federally funded Medicaid programs, for people with low incomes, offer coverage. And employers and insurers that provide commercial coverage are wary of paying for these drugs in part because of the large number of patients that might use them. The $500 monthly price for higher doses of the treatments also makes them unaffordable for those without insurance, doctors say. Medicare now covers the cost of the drugs for conditions such as type 2 diabetes and cardiovascular disease, but not for weight loss alone. Trump showing he is in touch with cost-of-living concerns The effort to lower costs barriers to popular GLP-1 drugs comes as the White House is looking to demonstrate that Trump is in touch with Americans frustrations with rising costs for food, housing, health care and other necessities. Republican gubernatorial candidates in New Jersey and Virginia faced a drubbing in Tuesdays election in which dour voter outlook about the economy appeared to an animating factor in the races. Roughly half of Virginia voters said the economy was the top issue, and about 6 in 10 of these voters picked Democrat Abigail Spanberger for governor, powering her to a decisive win, according to an AP voter poll. In New Jersey, Democrat Mikie Sherrill won about two-thirds of voters who called the economy the top issue facing the state, the poll found. She defeated a Trump-endorsed Republican candidate Jack Ciattarelli. More than half of New York City voters said the cost of living was the top issue facing the city. The Democratic mayor-elect Zohran Mamdani won about two-thirds of this group. The White House sought to diminish the effort by the previous Democratic administration as a gift to the pharmaceutical industry because the proposal did not include adequate price concessions from the drug makers. Trump, instead, consummated a belt and suspenders deal that ensures that Americans arent unfairly financing the pharmaceutical industrys innovation, claimed a senior administration official, who briefed reporters ahead of Thursdays Oval Office announcement by Trump. Another senior administration official said coverage of the drugs will expand to Medicare patients starting next year. Those who qualify will pay $50 copays for the medicine. Lower prices also will be phased in for people without coverage through the administrations TrumpRx program, which will allow people to buy drugs directly from manufacturers. starting in January. The officials said lower prices also will be provided for state and federally funded Medicaid programs. And starting doses of new, pill versions of the obesity treatments will cost $149 a month if they are approved. The officials briefed reporters on the condition of anonymity under ground rules set by the White House. Doctors applaud the price drop Dr. Leslie Golden says she has roughly 600 patients taking one of these treatments, and 75%% or more struggle to afford them. Even with coverage, some face $150 copayments for refills. Every visit its, How long can we continue to do this. Whats the plan if I cant continue., said Golden, an obesity medicine specialist in Watertown, Wisconsin. Some of them are working additional jobs or delaying retirement so they can continue to pay for it. Both Lilly and Novo have already cut prices on their drugs. Lilly said earlier this year it would reduce the cost of initial doses of Zepbound to $349. The potential to cover the medication for the 30 million people on Medicare who have obesity would be welcome, said Dr. Fatima Cody Stanford, an obesity expert at Massachusetts General Hospital. But until details are released, she remains skeptical. I would have to see it to believe it, she said. I need to see something that is more definitive for Medicare beneficiaries. I need to see something that is tangible and sustainable. Dr. Angela Fitch, who also treats patients with obesity, said she hoped a deal between the White House and drugmakers could be the first step in making the treatments more affordable. We need a hero in obesity care today, said Fitch, founder and chief medical officer of knownwell, a weight-loss and medical care company. The community has faced relentless barriers to accessing GLP-1 medications, which has ultimately come down to the price, despite the data we have supporting their effectiveness. text: Today, as we commemorate World Diabetes Day, we are reminded that diabetes remains one of the most urgent health challenges in our country. Its growing prevalence affects families, communities, and our entire healthcare system. That is why our mission is clear: Prevention must be our priority. This Agham Kapihan, together with Diabetes Philippines and AstraZeneca Philippines , marks an important milestone as we officially launch the STOP DIABETES: ACT NOW Program. This initiative highlights the need for early action, because diabetes and its complications can be prevented when we intervene early, educate communities, and empower patients to take control of their health. We also recognize the vital support of Philippine Health Insurance Corporation , whose YAKAP Program strengthens early diagnosis by providing essential tests for high-risk individuals. Early detection saves lives, reduces complications, and prevents many Filipinos from progressing to kidney disease and other serious outcomes. Most importantly, today is about partnership. We stand here together with patient groups, the Philippine Diabetes Support community and the Dialysis PH Support Group Inc. We remind that the fight against diabetes and chronic kidney disease is not only a medical battle, but a personal one. ğŸ¤ When government agencies, healthcare providers, patient groups, and private organizations unite, we create a stronger, more hopeful path forward. Together, we can stop diabetes. Together, we can protect Filipino families from CKD. Together, we act now. Thank you, and may this Kapihan inspire stronger collaboration and real change for all Filipinos at risk and living with diabetes. #WorldDiabetesDay2025 #TaraNaStopDiabetes ğŸ– #ACTNow P. S Nice meeting you all What's Up Today , Mommie Kleyrr #nofussmom, and FPJ Jr . It was a great discussion with you about Diabetes prevention and Kidney health. We hope we can work together to help spread accurate information on the importance of prevention and proper health management. Looking forward to future collaborations! - Reynaldo Segarra Abacan Jr. President of Dialysis PH ( Kabato Rey )

Today l had the pleasure of hosting Chairman of Merck Foundation Board of Trustees Professor Dr Frank Stangenberg-Haverkamp and Senator Dr Rasha Kelej, CEO of Merck Foundation and President of the â€œMore Than a Motherâ€ campaign.

We shared the milestones we achieved in healthcare, media, and girlsâ€™ education among other sectors over the past 7 years. Together, we are building a stronger, healthier, and more educated Zimbabwe for the future.

I am glad that our partnership through my Angel of Hope Foundation has resulted in Zimbabwe benefitting 166 scholarships empowering doctors in critical and underserved specialties such as diabetes, cardiology, oncology and fertility.

What is more pleasing is that our all weather friend Merck Foundation has doubled our yearly scholarships from 20 to 40 due to our strong dedication over the years.

As a champion for women empowerment l am also glad that through our partnership â€œEducating Lindaâ€ programme also continues to support 40 underprivileged high-performing girls yearly.

Indiana: Expansion of continuous manufacturing facilities in Mount Vernon.
California: A next-generation cell therapy manufacturing facility in Tarzana.
Job Creation: The investment is expected to create tens of thousands of new, highly skilled direct and indirect jobs across the country.
Context: This commitment is part of a broader trend among pharmaceutical companies to reshore operations to the U.S., influenced by the potential for new tariffs on imported medicines and a desire to strengthen the domestic supply chain.

text: Posted by Dr. Karl Goldkamp A borrowed message that sees the medical world as it is, unfortunately. Clearly we are not all diabetics but most of us are to some degree affected by the consequences of our inherited process food diet of the past 70 years. And, all of us probably know at least 1 person who is diabetic. I post this below merely to remind us our health is really determined by us, individually: learning, questioning, assessing, making changes. That's just the way it is and we all have to do it. The borrowed post: "We need to have an honest conversation about the American Diabetes Association. The ADA is seen as the official authority for diabetes care â€” but itâ€™s heavily funded by companies who profit when diabetes is lifelong and progressive, not reversed. Here are just some confirmed corporate sponsors and partners of the ADA: Eli Lilly â€” insulin + GLP-1 drugs Novo Nordisk â€” insulin + Ozempic/Wegovy Sanofi â€” insulin + diabetes meds AstraZeneca â€” SGLT2 drugs, statins, cardiometabolic meds Boehringer Ingelheim â€” diabetes & heart meds PepsiCo â€” soda + ultra-processed snacks Coca-Cola â€” long-time health organization funder Kelloggâ€™s â€” high-glycemic cereals and snack foods DaVita â€” one of the largest dialysis corporations in the U.S. Fresenius Medical Care â€” another dialysis giant These are not neutral supporters. These are corporations whose business models depend on rising insulin dependence, metabolic damage, and organ failure â€¦.not reversal. And the human cost is brutal: Nearly 40 million Americans currently have diabetes 50% will develop nerve damage 160,000 amputations every single year â€” the majority diabetes-related Dialysis is now a $100+ BILLION industry â€” and diabetes is the #1 cause Instead of aggressively prioritizing remission or prevention, the ADA continues to normalize long-term decline, even sharing emotional stories of people â€œfighting throughâ€ dialysis, blindness, amputations â€” as if this is just the natural path of the disease. "

text: Greetings everyone, Having never been a Facebook user I decided based on current life changes that it is time to start. I have been, to my mind, happily married for the last 5.5 years to Mickey Regenold. A nurse I worked with at Park Center prior to my wife of 21 years dying of Cancer in 2018. To my great surprise Mickey told me one month ago she was divorcing me. No discussion and no explanation. To this day I do not know why she is divorcing me. But it is clear that our time together has come to an end. I will walk away with gratitude for the 7 years we have shared together and with love in my heart. The following changes are in motion. Divorce will be final on Jan 15, 2026. I am buying a house in Kendallville, IN which is only about 8 miles from where I work. It should close on 12/15/25 and I anticipate moving in over Christmas s. I work at a CMHC as a psychiatrist and I work M - Thursday. I am also a national speaker for Bristol Myers Squibb on their new Schizophrenic drug, Cobenfy. On the personal side I have concluded that the main reason the marriage failed was because of a lack of good communication. Wherever something came up that involved any emotions, Mickey would shut down and refuse to talk about it. Over 5 years this amounted to more and more broken communications that could never have a complete cycle to finish them. I believe this broke the marriage. There are more issues that involve personal history which I am not at liberty to discuss. I will be looking to explore future relationships. Important issues for me are: #1 good communication, #2 I enjoy touch and have felt a severe absence of this in my marriage, $3 I would enjoy being able to discuss politics - for this reason I will not date anyone who voted for Trump. I understand that living in Indiana this limits me to a much smaller percentage of the populaton - but I accept that. Such is my update for now.

Hi, fam and friends. As some of you may have known, I was diagnosed with Stage 3 Cecal Mucinous Adenocarcinoma (Colorectal Cancer) last November 2022. I have tried herbal medicines for a while, but unfortunately, none of them have worked for me. My oncologist then advised me to undergo immunotherapy as he believes this is a better approach considering the type of cancer I have. It took my family some convincing, but finally, they agreed to let me pursue this treatment. I have high hopes that this would work for me, but I have to admit, I'm super worried as this therapy is expensive. Weâ€™re happy to be able to get a discount for Keytruda Patient Access Program (KEYPAP), the medicine for the treatment. However, even with this discount, the costs are still significant due to the number of sessions I need to complete (4-6 sessions every three weeks) and the frequency of PET CT scans required for reevaluation. Weâ€™re also applying for government assistance but weâ€™re unsure if help would arrive on time. In light of this, I find myself humbly reaching out for your support. Any financial help you can offer would greatly help as I begin with the treatment. And if you could keep me in your thoughts and prayers, that would mean so much. I know so many of us are facing tough times and I sincerely wish our circumstances are better.. So truly, thank you so much for your kindness and taking the time to read this. Lack of transparency..

â€”â€”-

The underlying issue is equally serious: 

residual plasmid DNA contamination has indeed been detected in Gardasil vials by independent scientists, and it raises deep questions about vaccine manufacturing oversight and transparency.

Letâ€™s walk carefully through whatâ€™s known, whatâ€™s been independently verified, and why the institutional reaction has been evasive.

 The core issue: plasmid DNA contamination in Gardasil

Gardasil is produced using recombinant DNA technology. 

The vaccine antigenâ€”the HPV L1 major capsid proteinâ€”is made by inserting the gene that codes for it into a plasmid vector, which is then expressed in yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) or in the quadrivalent/nonavalent versions, in insect cells (baculovirus system).

That plasmid serves as the genetic template for producing the virus-like particle (VLP) protein. After expression and purification, the plasmid DNA is supposed to be completely removed.

However, independent investigationsâ€”most famously by Dr. Sin Hang Lee, a molecular pathologist known for DNA sequencing integrityâ€”found that Gardasil vials contained residual HPV L1 gene fragments bound to aluminum adjuvant nanoparticles. 

In other words, pieces of residual plasmid DNA were still present and physically attached to aluminum hydroxyphosphate sulfate particles within the vaccine.

Why that matters

That discovery is not trivial. Aluminum adjuvants are known to form nano-sized aggregates that can:

â€¢Facilitate cellular uptake and slow release (so-called "depot effect"),

â€¢Potentially transport co-bound DNA into cells, where it could access nuclear compartments.

Residual foreign DNA, particularly when bound to a transfection-like adjuvant, introduces possible risks of:

1Genomic integration:
If those DNA fragments enter host cells, they can integrate into the genome under certain cellular conditions such as inflammation or oxidative stress. 

While the probability per cell may be low, the sheer number of doses administered globally magnifies the potential collective impact.

2Autoimmune reactions:

Persistent immune activation against foreign nucleic acids can trigger autoimmune responses, including molecular mimicry and chronic inflammation syndromes.

3Unknown long-term effects in younger populations:

HPV vaccination programs targeted preteens and teensâ€”populations with developing immune and endocrine systemsâ€”before long-term safety studies on DNA-aluminum complexes had been conducted.

What independent findings showed

Dr. Leeâ€™s group (operating independently, not industry-funded) used nested PCR and DNA sequencing on vials from several countries. 

They consistently detected HPV L1 gene sequencesâ€”not free-floating, but firmly bound to aluminum particles.

These results suggested that regulatory-quality testing either failed to detect the contamination or ignored it.

When Lee published and submitted evidence to the WHO, FDA, and CDC, the response was bureaucratic deflection:

â€¢WHOâ€™s Global Advisory Committee on Vaccine Safety dismissed it as â€œbiologically insignificant.â€

â€¢No independent retesting of Gardasil lots was conducted under public oversight.

â€¢Instead, Leeâ€™s credibility was attacked rather than his data refuted.

Then, in retrospective litigation discovery (e.g., cases brought over Gardasil adverse effects such as postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome or chronic fatigue syndromes), it became clear that Merckâ€™s internal toxicology pipeline had not required assays for DNA-aluminum complexesâ€”a major regulatory blind spot.

Institutional problem, not just a technical one

This isnâ€™t just about trace DNA; itâ€™s about transparency and quality control.

â€¢Both the U.S. FDA and European Medicines Agency (EMA) have thresholds for residual DNA in biologics (10 ng/dose for biotechnological products; even stricter for vaccines).

Yet, no publicly available data confirm that Gardasil consistently met these limits across batch lots.

Mentioned in the Paper
- **Limited Data on Certain Vaccine Doses**: The number of individuals receiving a booster dose of ChAdOx1 (AstraZeneca) or mRNA-1273 (Moderna) was too small to reliably evaluate myocarditis risk for these specific scenarios. This reduces the precision and applicability of findings for booster doses of these vaccines.
Potential Misclassification of Outcomes
Myocarditis was identified solely through ICD-10 codes from hospital admissions or death certifications. This reliance on administrative coding could lead to over- or underestimation of true incidence due to diagnostic errors, inconsistent coding practices, or missed mild cases not requiring hospitalization. The authors note: "Reliance on hospital admission codes and death certification for defining myocarditis may lead to over- or underestimation due to misclassification."
Small Subgroup Sizes: In the 13-17 years age group, only 56 myocarditis events occurred overall, with just 16 post-vaccination. This low event count precluded separate risk evaluations for this subgroup, limiting insights into adolescent-specific risks.
Exclusion of Recurrent Events: The analysis focused only on the first myocarditis occurrence, so results for third (booster) doses do not account for repeated events in the same individuals, potentially underestimating cumulative risk.
Inability to Compare Mortality Outcomes**: The study restricted analyses to vaccinated individuals, making it impossible to directly compare myocarditis-related death rates between infected (unvaccinated) and vaccinated groups. This may underestimate mortality risks specifically after SARS-CoV-2 infection alone.
Precision Issues with mRNA-1273
Fewer people received mRNA-1273 compared to other vaccines, and recipients were on average younger (mean age ~32 years vs. mid-40s/50s for others). This smaller sample size reduced statistical precision for this vaccine, and the age difference could confound observed higher risks, as younger age is a known risk factor for vaccine-associated myocarditis.
Inferred Flaws and Weaknesses Based on Study Design
While the authors conducted robustness checks (e.g., sensitivity analyses for reporting delays and exclusions), the design introduces other potential issues:
Incomplete Capture of SARS-CoV-2 Infections**: Only 13.9% of the vaccinated population had a positive test recorded, likely due to under-testing. This could bias comparisons between infection- and vaccination-related risks, as many infections may have gone undetected, leading to underestimation of infection-attributable myocarditis.
Unmeasured Confounders
Adjustments were made for age, sex, and calendar time, but factors like comorbidities, genetic predispositions, prior infections, or behavioral differences (e.g., healthcare-seeking patterns) were not accounted for. In a self-controlled design, this is partially mitigated by within-person comparisons, but residual confounding remains possible, especially for time-varying exposures.
Temporal and Generalizability Constraints Data covered December 2020 to December 2021, capturing early pandemic waves and initial vaccine rollouts with specific variants (e.g., Alpha/Delta). Results may not generalize to later periods with Omicron variants, updated vaccines, or different populations outside England (e.g., varying demographics, healthcare systems, or vaccination policies). The study also excludes unvaccinated individuals for direct infection-risk comparisons.
Short Observation Windows and Event Rarity Risk intervals were limited to 1-28 days post-exposure, potentially missing longer-term effects. With only 2,861 total myocarditis cases (0.007% of the population), rare events in subgroups amplify uncertainty in incidence rate ratios (IRRs), even if overall estimates are robust.
Self-Controlled Case Series Biases This design assumes events are independent across periods and that individuals serve as their own controls

Blocking a single protein forces cancer cells to self-destruct Date: November 20, 2025 Source: NYU Langone Health / NYU Grossman School of Medicine Summary: Researchers uncovered a powerful weakness in lung cancer by shutting down a protein that helps tumors survive stress. When this protein, FSP1, was blocked, lung tumors in mice shrank dramatically, with many cancer cells essentially triggering their own self-destruct mode. The work points to a fresh strategy for targeting stubborn lung cancers. Share: FULL STORY Protein Block Makes Cancer Self-Destruct Stopping one protein forces lung cancer cells to self-destruct. Credit: Shutterstock Researchers at NYU Langone Health have identified how a specific form of cell death linked to the buildup of highly reactive molecules can slow the growth of lung tumors. This type of cell death, known as ferroptosis, originally evolved as a way for the body to clear out cells that become overly stressed. Cancer cells fall into this category, yet over time they have developed ways to block ferroptosis so they can continue multiplying even under damaging conditions. Blocking FSP1 Dramatically Weakens Lung Tumors A study published online November 5 in Nature showed that an experimental therapy targeting a protein called ferroptosis suppressor protein 1 (FSP1) significantly reduced tumor growth in mice with lung adenocarcinoma (LUAD). Blocking this protein, which helps cancer cells avoid ferroptosis, shrank tumors by as much as 80%. Lung cancer remains the world's leading cause of cancer-related deaths, and LUAD is the most common form among nonsmokers, accounting for about 40% of cases. "This first test of a drug that blocks ferroptosis suppression highlights the importance of the process to cancer cell survivaland paves the way for a new treatment strategy," said senior study author Thales Papagiannakopoulos, PhD[GW1], an associate professor in the Department of Pathology[GW2] at the NYU Grossman School of Medicine. Reactive Molecules and Their Role in Cell Damage Ferroptosis takes place when iron levels rise inside cells, fueling the production of highly reactive molecules made from oxygen, water, and hydrogen peroxide known as reactive oxygen species (ROS). In small amounts, ROS help cells communicate. In excess, they create oxidative stress, which occurs when ROS add oxygen molecules to vital proteins and DNA, damaging or breaking them apart. ROS can also harm fats that form the outer membranes of cells, contributing to cell death and tissue injury. Blocking FSP1 Shows Strong Tumor-Suppressing Effects To investigate how FSP1 affects lung cancer, the research team genetically modified mice so that their lung cancer cells lacked the FSP1 gene. These mice developed smaller tumors due to increased cancer cell death. The researchers also tested icFSP1, a newer drug designed to inhibit FSP1. Mice treated with icFSP1 lived longer and experienced tumor reductions similar to those seen in mice whose cancer cells were engineered to lack FSP1. The study also found that FSP1 may be a more promising treatment target than another ferroptosis-blocking protein, glutathione peroxidase 4 (GPX4), which has been studied in cancer research for a longer period. The findings suggest that FSP1 is more actively involved in preventing ferroptosis in lung cancer cells while playing a smaller role in normal cell function (which could translate to fewer side effects). Increased levels of FSP1 were also associated with poorer survival rates in human LUAD patients, unlike GPX4. Future Directions and Ongoing Research "Our future research will focus on optimizing FSP1 inhibitors and investigating the potential of harnessing ferroptosis as a treatment strategy for other solid tumors, such as pancreatic cancer," said lead study author Katherine Wu, an MD/PhD student working in the Papagiannakopoulos lab. "We aim to translate these findings from the lab into novel clinical therapies for cancer patients." In addition to Wu and Pagagiannakopoulos, contributors from the Department of Pathology at NYU Langone include co-first author Alec Vaughan, Jozef Bossowski, Yuan Hao, Aikaterini Ziogou, Mari Nakamura, Ray Pillai, Mariana Mancini, Sahith Rajalingam, and Suckwoo Chung. Other study authors include Seon Min Kim, Tae Ha Kim, and Yun Pyo Kang of the College of Pharmacy and Research Institute of Pharmaceutical Sciences at Seoul National University; Mingqi Han and David Shackelford from the Department of Pulmonary and Critical Care Medicine at the David Geffen School of Medicine, University of California Los Angeles; Toshitaka Nakamura and Marcus Conrad of the Institute of Metabolism and Cell Death, Molecular Targets and Therapeutics Center at Helmholtz Munich in Germany; and Lidong Wang and Diane Simeone of the Moores Cancer Center, University of California, San Diego, La Jolla. The study received funding from National Institutes of Health grants S10RR027926, S10OD032292, R37CA222504, R01CA227649, R01CA283049, R01CA262562, T32GM136542, T32GM136573, and T32GM136542. Additional support was provided by the American Cancer Society Research Scholar Grant (RSG-17-20001-TBE), the Ruth L. Kirschstein Individual Predoctoral National Research Service Award fellowship (F30CA275258), the Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG) (CO 291/7-1 Priority Program SPP 2306 [CO 291/9-1, #461385412; CO 291/10-1, #461507177], the European Research Council under the European Union's Horizon 2020 research and innovation program (grant GA 884754), and the Perlmutter Cancer Center Support Grant P30CA016087. Papagiannakopoulos received funding from the Pfizer Medical Education Group, Dracen Pharmaceuticals, Kymera Therapeutics, Bristol Myers Squibb, and Agios available under an aCC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 international license. These relationships are being managed in accordance with NYU Langone Health policies. Story Source: Materials provided by NYU Langone Health / NYU Grossman School of Medicine. Note: Content may be edited for style and length. Journal Reference: Katherine Wu, Alec J. Vaughan, Jozef P. Bossowski, Yuan Hao, Aikaterini Ziogou, Seon Min Kim, Tae Ha Kim, Mari N. Nakamura, Ray Pillai, Mariana Mancini, Sahith Rajalingam, Mingqi Han, Toshitaka Nakamura, Lidong Wang, Suckwoo Chung, Diane Simeone, David Shackelford, Yun Pyo Kang, Marcus Conrad, Thales Papagiannakopoulos. Targeting FSP1 triggers ferroptosis in lung cancer. Nature, 2025; DOI: 10.1038/s41586-025-09710-8 Cite This Page: MLA APA Chicago NYU Langone Health / NYU Grossman School of Medicine. "Blocking a single protein forces cancer cells to self-destruct." ScienceDaily. ScienceDaily, 20 November 2025. <www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/11/251120002606.htm>.

When Josephine Dickson's kitchen accidents became a regular occurrence in 1920, her husband Earle created a solution that would change first aid forever. Earle was a cotton buyer for Johnson & Johnson in New Jersey. He noticed his wife was always cutting or burning her fingers while cooking. Back then, dressing a small wound by yourself was a clumsy process, involving separate gauze and tape. So, Earle came up with a simple idea. He took a long strip of his company's adhesive tape, laid a strip of gauze down the middle, and covered it with crinoline fabric to keep it sterile and prevent the adhesive from sticking to itself. Now, his wife Josephine could simply cut off a piece and apply a bandage herself whenever she had a minor accident in the kitchen. ğŸ©¹ He showed the invention to his bosses at Johnson & Johnson. They were impressed by the simple practicality of the idea and decided to produce it. The first commercial "Band-Aids" were sold in 1921. Sales were slow at first, though. The first year, they only sold about $3,000 worth of the new product, because most people were not yet familiar with the idea of a pre-made bandage. The company didn't give up. They decided to give them away to Boy Scout troops and butchers to demonstrate their usefulness. The strategy worked, and popularity soared. ğŸ‡ºğŸ‡¸ That small solution, born out of a husband's care for his wife, is now found in nearly every home, school, and workplace in the country. A true American success story. Sources: Lemelson-MIT Program, National Inventors Hall of Fame, Johnson & Johnson website

text: Johnson & Johnson Faces 60,000+ Lawsuits in UK Over Talc-Based Baby Powder Allegedly Linked to Cancer London, UK: In a growing legal battle, pharmaceutical giant Johnson & Johnson is facing an alarming number of lawsuits in the United Kingdom, with 60,000 to 67,000 plaintiffs accusing the company of selling talc-based baby powder products that allegedly caused cancer. The primary allegations center around claims that the talc used in their products was contaminated with Asbestos, a known carcinogen, leading to deadly cancers, particularly Ovarian cancer and Mesothelioma (a rare form of cancer often linked to asbestos exposure). The lawsuits have garnered widespread attention, with plaintiffs alleging that prolonged use of Johnson & Johnsonâ€™s talc-based powders, especially in the genital area, contributed to their cancer diagnoses. The plaintiffs claim that the company failed to adequately warn consumers about the risks associated with talc, despite mounting evidence linking talc to cancer. Allegations of Asbestos Contamination Central to the legal claims is the allegation that talc a mineral often used in cosmetic and personal care products was contaminated with traces of Asbestos. Asbestos is a naturally occurring substance that has been proven to cause various forms of cancer, including Lung cancer, Mesothelioma and Ovarian cancer. Plaintiffs argue that Johnson & Johnson's failure to remove asbestos from their talc-based powders or provide adequate warnings contributed to their illnesses. Over the years, the company has faced growing scrutiny regarding the safety of its talc products. In 2018, an Investigation revealed that traces of asbestos were found in some batches of Johnson & Johnsonâ€™s talc. Although Johnson & Johnson has continuously maintained that its products are safe, the ongoing legal actions continue to fuel public concern about the potential health risks of talc-based powders. Johnson & Johnsonâ€™s Response In response to the numerous lawsuits, Johnson & Johnson has firmly rejected the claims, maintaining that its talc-based baby powder is safe and does not cause cancer. The company argues that multiple scientific studies and tests have concluded that their products do not contain asbestos and are free from any cancer causing substances. However, the companyâ€™s position has not stopped the growing tide of litigation. In 2020, in response to both legal and consumer pressures, Johnson & Johnson announced that it would stop selling its talc-based baby powder in the United States and Canada, opting instead to focus on cornstarch based alternatives. The move was seen as a way to address consumer concerns, though the company maintained that the decision was not an admission of guilt regarding cancer risk. The Los Angeles Lawsuit Verdict The legal troubles for Johnson & Johnson recently escalated when a Los Angeles jury ordered the company to pay a staggering $966 million in damages to a woman who claimed that her use of the talc-based baby powder caused her to develop ovarian cancer. This ruling added significant weight to the ongoing legal challenges and sparked further public debate over the safety of talc in personal care products. The case in Los Angeles was just one of many ongoing lawsuits, with plaintiffs in the UK and other parts of the world continuing to seek justice for the alleged health risks associated with Johnson & Johnsonâ€™s talc products. Health Awareness and Consumer Safety The controversy surrounding talc-based products has raised important health awareness concerns, especially for consumers who have used these products over an extended period of time. Health professionals have long warned about the potential risks of asbestos exposure, and the growing body of legal evidence linking talc to cancer has prompted calls for more stringent regulation and clearer consumer warnings. Consumers are encouraged to carefully review the ingredients in personal care products and to be aware of any Possible health risks associated with their use. People who have used talc-based baby powder or similar products for years and are experiencing symptoms of ovarian cancer or other related health conditions should consult with a healthcare provider for guidance and potential testing. As the legal battle continues, the focus remains on the safety and regulation of personal care products, as well as the responsibility of corporations to ensure that their products do not pose harm to consumers. Looking Ahead The future of Johnson & Johnsonâ€™s talc products remains uncertain as more lawsuits are expected to surface in the coming months. The company faces mounting pressure from plaintiffs and health advocates who argue that the public deserves greater transparency and accountability from manufacturers. With the legal outcome still pending, many are left questioning the safety of talc-based products and the impact they have on public health. Johnson & Johnsonâ€™s Response In response to the numerous lawsuits, Johnson & Johnson has firmly rejected the claims, maintaining that its talc-based baby powder is safe and does not cause cancer. The company argues that multiple scientific studies and tests have concluded that their products do not contain asbestos and are free from any cancer causing substances. However, the companyâ€™s position has not stopped the growing tide of litigation. In 2020, in response to both legal and consumer pressures, Johnson & Johnson announced that it would stop selling its talc-based baby powder in the United States and Canada, opting instead to focus on cornstarch based alternatives. The move was seen as a way to address consumer concerns, though the company maintained that the decision was not an admission of guilt regarding cancer risk. The Los Angeles Lawsuit Verdict The legal troubles for Johnson & Johnson recently escalated when a Los Angeles jury ordered the company to pay a staggering $966 million in damages to a woman who claimed that her use of the talc-based baby powder caused her to develop ovarian cancer. This ruling added significant weight to the ongoing legal challenges and sparked further public debate over the safety of talc in personal care products. The case in Los Angeles was just one of many ongoing lawsuits, with plaintiffs in the UK and other parts of the world continuing to seek justice for the alleged health risks associated with Johnson & Johnsonâ€™s talc products. Health Awareness and Consumer Safety The controversy surrounding talc-based products has raised important health awareness concerns, especially for consumers who have used these products over an extended period of time. Health professionals have long warned about the potential risks of asbestos exposure, and the growing body of legal evidence linking talc to cancer has prompted calls for more stringent regulation and clearer consumer warnings. Consumers are encouraged to carefully review the ingredients in personal care products and to be aware of any Possible health risks associated with their use. People who have used talc-based baby powder or similar products for years and are experiencing symptoms of ovarian cancer or other related health conditions should consult with a healthcare provider for guidance and potential testing. As the legal battle continues, the focus remains on the safety and regulation of personal care products, as well as the responsibility of corporations to ensure that their products do not pose harm to consumers. Looking Ahead The future of Johnson & Johnsonâ€™s talc products remains uncertain as more lawsuits are expected to surface in the coming months. The company faces mounting pressure from plaintiffs and health advocates who argue that the public deserves greater transparency and accountability from manufacturers. With the legal outcome still pending, many are left questioning the safety of talc-based products and the impact they have on public health. #NTH_CARES BRONCHOSCOPY MACHINE BOOSTS LUNG CANCER DIAGNOSTICS AT NDOLA TEACHING HOSPITAL ======================== Ndola Teaching Hospital has strengthened its respiratory diagnostic capacity following the official handover of a bronchoscopy machine and accompanying digital equipment valued at over K700,000. The donation was made through the Multinational Lung Cancer Control Program (MLCCP), implemented by Access to Health Zambia and Zambart, with support from the Bristol Myers Squibb Foundation. Speaking during the ceremony, Copperbelt Provincial Health Director, Dr. Charles Mwinuna, represented by Dr. Nasilele Simushi, described the donation as a major step toward improving early detection and management of lung cancer, tuberculosis, and other respiratory conditions on the Copperbelt. He said the bronchoscopy machine represents more than a technological upgrade, stressing that it symbolizes progress, innovation, and the power of collaboration in improving public health outcomes. â€œBronchoscopy is a critical diagnostic tool that enables clinicians to detect lung abnormalities early. By enhancing diagnostic capacity here in the Copperbelt, we move a step closer to reducing the burden of respiratory diseases and improving patient outcomes,â€ he said. Dr. Mwinuna applauded Access to Health Zambia and Zambart for their leadership in research and health system strengthening, stating that their partnership with Ndola Teaching Hospital demonstrates how collaboration can deliver meaningful healthcare solutions. He urged the hospitalâ€™s management and clinical staff to ensure optimal use and proper maintenance of the machine to improve service delivery. â€œAs we receive this bronchoscopy machine, let us renew our commitment to advancing health equity, investing in technology, and building a resilient healthcare system for the people of Zambia,â€ he added. Access to Health Zambia Chief Executive Officer, Mrs. Batuke Walusiku-Mwewa, said the donation aligns with national efforts to combat cancer and expand specialized healthcare services. She highlighted that the partnership with Zambart and the Ministry of Health under the MLCCP has strengthened cancer awareness, trained community health workers, and expanded lung cancer screening in Ndola and Kabwe. â€œAs part of this ongoing work, we are proud to hand over a bronchoscopy machine, laptops, tablets, and a desktop computer to enhance diagnostics, data management, and research,â€ she said. Zambart Executive Director, Dr. Kwame Shanaube, commended the partnership, noting that improved diagnostic equipment is essential for reducing delays in lung cancer detection and improving treatment outcomes. She emphasized that bronchoscopy capacity at Ndola Teaching Hospital will help reduce misdiagnosis and delays in patient care. Meanwhile, Ndola Teaching Hospital Acting Head Clinical Care, Dr. Tela Bulaya, thanked Zambart, Access to Health Zambia, and the Bristol Myers Squibb Foundation for the donation, describing it as a milestone in advancing the hospitalâ€™s respiratory services. â€œFor years, patients suspected of having lung cancer or other respiratory complications had to be referred to Lusaka at great financial and emotional cost,â€ she said. â€œToday, that burden has been lifted. This machine brings life-saving diagnostic services closer to the people.â€ Dr. Bulaya assured partners that the equipment will be properly maintained and fully utilized, supported through continuous staff training. She also acknowledged the efforts of the Internal Medicine, Respiratory, and Biomedical Engineering teams whose dedication made the milestone possible. The newly commissioned bronchoscopy machine is expected to significantly improve diagnostic accuracy, reduce referral delays, and strengthen Ndola Teaching Hospitalâ€™s role as a regional centre for specialized healthcare services. By :Ndola Teaching Hospital Public Relations Department
